Introduction
What comes to your mind when you think of small talk? You may think of
the awkward and boring side of small talk, or you may think of it as a
conversation lifesaver. In this book, we’ll be exploring the latter, as small
talk really is a conversation necessity that can help you through so many
situations in your life.
We often overlook small talk, as we think it’s a time filler that can be quite
tedious and annoying. With this perspective of small talk, you fail to notice
how much you can learn, discover, and achieve from it. It has so many
benefits and functions that can aid conversations, as well as your personal
connections in life.
Do you want to make new friendships, you’re ready for a romantic
relationship, or you want to get close to your colleagues? Using small talk
effectively is the first step to help you achieve all of these things. By
breaking the ice with small talk, you’re able to connect with people on a
deeper level and form those emotional connections you desire.
Small talk is essentially the foundation of effective communication. You
can’t have those important conversations, relationship-building moments,
and retrieve valuable information through conversation without starting
with small talk first. Using small talk breaks the ice and allows room for
your conversation to build and grow from there.
Becoming a master of small talk means that you can leave all awkwardness
and tension behind, as you’re able to bring up effective conversation topics
at any given time. You’ll feel more confident in yourself to break the
silence, and once you do, people will be impressed by how skilled you are
at clearing the air and starting conversation.
Through this book, you’ll learn all the necessary skills that will help you to
generate small talk. You will learn how to start conversations and keep them
going seamlessly. This book will also help you to strengthen your
relationships, start new ones, and form emotional connections: all with the
use of small talk.
CHAPTER 1
Small Talk 101
"Small talk is the biggest talk we do." – Susan RoAne
The power of small talk is a lot greater than you may think. Although you
may view it as superficial, even pointless, it can do a lot of good for your
conversation skills. When you master small talk, you’ll be able to utilize it
in many scenarios in your life.
We’ve all been in a situation where we have no idea how to start a
conversation. There’s an immense amount of awkward silence that is
deafening, but you have no idea how to get the conversation ball rolling.
Utilizing small talk is the best way to get a conversation started. Although
small talk can be tedious and annoying at times, it provides a valuable
conversational tool that can help you eliminate that awkward silence.
The Small Talk Mindset
To engage in small talk successfully, you need to get your mindset in the
right place. We often forget how our thoughts and mental attitude influence
how we communicate with others. This makes it imperative that you have a
small talk mindset that helps you to utilize it to the best of your ability. Like
many other individuals, you may be thinking to yourself, What is the point
of small talk? Having this mindset won’t get you the results you desire.
You must understand that small talk has a valuable purpose within your
conversations so that you can get into the right mindset of using it. You
need to let go of the mindset that small talk is awkward and should be
avoided at all costs, and start embracing that it’s the foundation of all good
conversation.
What Is the Foundation of Good Communication?
To get into the mindset of using small talk, you need to understand what the
foundation of good communication is. When you think of communication,
what would you consider to be the foundation and base of successful
communication? You may say good listening skills, conversation starters, or
empathetic communication, but what truly acts as a foundation to our
communication is small talk. We don’t realize how much small talk actually
helps the ball get rolling when it comes to communicating.
If you’re reading this book, you’re here to learn how to be a better
communicator. You want to build connections, develop the ones you have,
and introduce yourself to new people. All of this can be achieved by
mastering the use of small talk. Essentially, small talk acts as the foundation
of effective communication that connects you with others. You need to be
able to start at the bottom with small talk, to work your way up to
meaningful and life-changing conversation.
The Benefits of Small Talk
You may be the type of person who tries to avoid small talk at all costs
because you find it so boring and mundane. However, you could be
overlooking the true benefits of utilizing small talk. With that being said,
there’s a time and place for using small talk that can be most beneficial for
your conversation skills. You need to utilize small talk in the best way
possible, to reap the benefits you desire from it. This is a brief touch on all
the benefits you can experience, as they will be discussed in greater detail
throughout the book.
Breaking the Ice
We’ve all found ourselves in an awkward situation where we have no idea
how to start a conversation organically. The more time passes, the more
awkward it is to try and break the ice. Utilizing small talk is a quick and
easy way to break the ice naturally. You’re able to break that deafening
silence and instigate conversation.
Once you break the ice with small talk, you will find that conversation can
flow from there. You’re able to learn more about the person you’re talking
to, crack jokes, and even discuss personal matters. There’s so many
communication opportunities that can branch off of your small talk. All you
need is that general small talk to break the ice between you and another
individual.
Creating Valuable Connections
You never know how valuable someone could be in your life until you
reach out to them. We are often too fearful to approach individuals we don’t
know, as we find it too and scary to start conversation. You may be sitting
next to someone in a library, and they look like a fun individual you want to
get to know, or you are in the workplace and there’s a specific person
you’ve always wanted to become friends with. Although you want to reach
out to these people and form connections, you don’t know how to
accomplish it.
When you use small talk, you will find that it’s a lot easier to get out of
your comfort zone and form these valuable connections. You’re able to start
a conversation with the interesting looking person next to you in the
grocery store, and you can end up building valuable connections. Who
knows, maybe you make a connection with someone who could be valuable
for your career, or you form a relationship with someone who becomes your
best friend.
Finding Common Ground
Small talk is a valuable way to help you get closer to people, as you find
common ground. This is especially effective if you’re conversing with
someone you don’t know, as you may have no idea where to start with
conversation. You don’t know what this other person’s interests are and
how you can start communicating comfortably with each other.
It can be challenging to find common ground with someone through casual
conversation, but small talk allows you to discuss common topics. For
example, you may talk about a situation that you’re witnessing in front of
you. You may find this helps you to hear their opinion about the situation,
which may be similar to yours. You then know that you both relate on
something.
The Seven Principles of Dialogue
Before you learn how to use small talk in your everyday life, you need to be
able to conquer these principles first. Small talk is more than just talking
about the weather, as it can be a lot more meaningful when you consider the
principles of it. Small talk is just like any form of dialogue and there are
principles to it that need to be valued. These are the seven principles of
dialogue and why they’re so important:
1. Be respectful. The first and foremost important principle to consider is
being respectful to the people you talk to. We all want to be treated
with respect in our conversations, and this will only happen if you
show respect to others first, as it will be reciprocated to you. When you
bring up certain topics during small talk, make sure you’re respectful
when you bring them up, and avoid talking about sensitive and
controversial topics that may upset someone.
2. Avoid manipulating the conversation. When you’re communicating
with someone, you need to avoid using any toxic or manipulative
habits throughout the conversation. For example, if you want someone
to agree with something you’re saying, you shouldn’t use guilt-tripping
tactics to get what you want from them. Being manipulative during
conversations will only negatively impact you in the long run, and it
will not be healthy for your relationships overall.
3. Keep communication channels open. You may be the type of person
who expects other people to start conversations with you, but you
don’t make the effort to show that your communication channels are
open. In order to have effective communication, you need to keep
these channels open so that people feel comfortable talking to you.
You can show that your communication channels are open by being
receptive and open when people want to have a conversation with you.
You should also try to make the first step by talking to other people
first.
4. Each person is the speaker and listener. A conversation is a two-way
activity. It isn’t a conversation if you’re the only one talking or if
you’re not saying anything at all, so it’s imperative that you both
maintain a healthy speaking-to-listening ratio. This means that you
must speak at times and show the other person you’re engaged and
interested. However, you also mustn’t overdo it and talk nonstop. Give
the other person the time to talk and say what they want. If the person
you’re talking to isn’t speaking, you should ask them questions, to give
them the space to find their voice in your conversation.
5. Avoid monologues. Nobody likes a person who doesn’t know when to
stop talking. Your goal is to have a dialogue with someone, which
means that two people must be talking to each other. If you find
yourself continuously talking on your own, then you’re basically
performing a monologue. This will only bore the person you’re talking
to, as they can’t even get a word in. You need to prevent yourself from
getting into the monologue zone, as you need to open the floor for
other people to speak so that it can become dialogue.
6. Avoid negativity and judgment. Let’s be honest, as humans we can
be very judgmental and critical by nature. Although you may like to
say you never judge anyone, there’s a part of all of us that is often
guilty of judging people, especially based on first impressions. When
you’re trying to have open communication with people, you want to
prevent yourself from limiting the conversation by being judgmental
and critical. If someone is opening up to you, don’t criticize what they
did or judge them silently. You must rather listen to them with
empathy, and let go of your negative opinions.
7. Acknowledge the presence of others. There’s nothing more
humiliating or frustrating than feeling completely ignored in a
conversation. This can often happen in conversations with more than
two people. Two individuals can be chatting away nicely, while the
third or fourth individual is left behind in the dark. You never want to
make someone feel as though they are excluded from your
conversation. It’s important to at least acknowledge the presence of
everyone in the conversation, by giving them eye contact, asking them
questions, and directing the conversation toward them.
4 Key Elements of Small Talk
When you’re considering the principles of small talk, you must also take
into account the key elements of small talk. As with any form of
conversation, there are elements of small talk that are valuable to take note
of. These elements make up the content of your small talk and help you to
establish what forms of conversation to use within it. Using these elements
as you communicate will help you practice small talk with more ease:
Ask. The best way to make small talk a two-sided conversation is by
asking the other person questions. You may be engaging in small talk
by bringing general conversation topics up, but the other person may
not be entertaining it. You may find them simply agreeing, nodding
their heads, or giving one-word responses. By asking them interesting
questions, you help them to get more involved in the small talk. This
will make it more of a conversation, rather than you talking their ear
off.
Inform. When you’re practicing small talk, you may begin talking
about a topic you know very well, but the individual you’re talking to
isn’t as knowledgeable on this topic. This may cause you to go on and
on about the topic, while the other person is confused about what
you’re talking about. This makes it extremely important for you to
inform the person you’re talking to. If you bring up a topic, add some
context to it so that they understand what you’re talking about better.
Include. Successful small talk is when both parties feel included
throughout the conversation. To ensure that the individual you’re
talking to feels included in the conversation, you must be observant of
them. Instead of just talking and going off on a tangent, you must
monitor how the other person is responding or reacting. If you can see
their body language is disinterested, you must make more of an effort
to include them. Maybe ask them questions or change the topic to
something they’re more informed on.
Propose. Small talk doesn’t end at the general topic brought up, as the
conversation must build onto something else with more depth. You
need to be able to propose ways to steer the conversation into different
topics. For example, you may find yourself uncomfortable talking
about a specific topic, so when it’s brought up, you can steer the
conversation where you want it to be. You want to take control of the
conversation by directing it where you want it to go through proposals.
When you’re practicing small talk, you want to take into account these
elements so that you accomplish successful conversations with others.
Don’t be shy to commit to the small talk by asking questions when
necessary, including the other person by informing them, and making sure
they’re engaging in the conversation. You also mustn’t be afraid to steer the
conversation in another direction when you don’t feel comfortable with it.
Improving Your Conversational Skills
When it comes to having conversations, not everyone is a professional.
Although you try hard, you may not be the best at starting conversations or
continuing them. If this is something you struggle with, don’t worry,
because using small talk is just one way in which you can improve your
conversational skills. You don’t have to be the most confident and
charismatic individual, and you don’t need to be a very interesting person
with crazy topics to talk about; all you need are some small talk skills and
you’ll become a professional at starting and engaging in conversations. You
will notice that using small talk helps you to improve your conversational
skills in the following ways:
Learning social skills. Ultimately, building communication skills is
all about understanding social surroundings. We communicate based
on what’s happening around us. When you learn how to utilize small
talk effectively, you’re able to improve your social skills. You discover
when people want to be spoken to, as well as how you can get their
attention through conversation. These developed social skills will help
you to be an overall better communicator who is conscious of the
people around you.
Helps you to start conversations. You may be a more introverted or
shy individual who struggles to start conversations with people, and
learning how to use small talk will help you start conversations on
your own. Through small talk, you find simple and easy ways to start
conversations with others. Knowing how to use small talk effectively
will also help you to build confidence in yourself, which makes it
easier for you to start conversations and build connections.
Learning how to engage people. Are you the well-known rambler
that everyone tries to steer clear of? There’s nothing wrong with being
a chatterbox, but it’s important to give other people a chance. Learning
how to practice small talk effectively will teach you how to give other
people the spotlight. You know how to include other people in the
conversation and ask questions to engage people who aren’t involved
in the conversation. This will definitely make people more excited and
interested in talking to you.
Mastering small talk can teach you a lot about communicating and how to
improve your conversational skills. When you’re able to start conversations,
keep people engaged in conversation, and understand social skills, you’re
able to be the effective communicator you’ve always wanted to be. You
won’t only be able to engage in small talk, but you’ll find it easier to
participate in any form of conversation.
CHAPTER 2
Icebreakers and Small Talk
Approaches
"The right word at the right time will unlock the door of treasures- the wrong
one will close it forever." – Rasheed Ogunlaru
Have you ever found yourself in an awkward conversation with someone
where there’s long bouts of cold silence? You have no idea what to say to
break the silence and make things more comfortable. The longer the silence
is, the more difficult it is to come up with conversation starters to break the
ice. We’ve all found ourselves in this position in life, but did you know this
could all be easily avoided with the use of small talk.
Small talk can effectively be used to break the ice in a conversation, as
you’re able to connect on common topics that anybody would know about.
This makes the atmosphere less awkward, as you connect on a topic. From
there you’ll find it a lot easier to generate organic conversation. Learning
how to approach small talk is important, as it will help you to break the ice
in an appropriate manner.
How to Break the Ice
Nobody likes to be caught in an extremely awkward situation that is
completely silent. Both parties don’t know what to do to break the
overwhelming silence, so you stay in silence for what feels like a lifetime.
It’s important to learn how to break the silence with small talk so that you
can avoid these scenarios. You can’t get to know someone, build a
connection, or discover information if you don’t work on breaking the ice
first.
Introducing Yourself
If you find yourself in awkward silence with someone you’ve never met
before, you can start off by introducing yourself. You may be near someone
who looks fun and interesting, you’ve always wanted to be friends with
them, or you’re just interested in making more connections in your life.
Being able to introduce yourself properly is important because first
impressions matter. People gather what type of person you are by the way
you introduce yourself, so you should put some effort into it. This is how
you can introduce yourself successfully to break the silence:
Past: You’re probably used to hearing the boring and basic
introductions, where you simply say your name and where you’re from,
but introductions can be a lot more interesting when you try this
method. You can start off by saying your name and then tell them a fact
about your past. Giving them information about your past experiences
can intrigue them. For example, you can tell them about what you
studied in the past, or you can even talk about something recent that
happened in your life the day before.
Present: You should then bring up something about your present. You
may find that it’s more natural and sensical for you to start off by
bringing up something about your present, so you can do this first. You
can talk about something that is currently happening in your life , or
you can be literal and talk about something you’re experiencing at that
moment. For example, if you’re working next to someone in a coffee
shop, you can let them know what work you’re doing.
Future: You can then proceed to talk about something that is related to
your future. Letting people know about something you plan on doing in
the future can tell them a lot about you. You can be open about your
passion for your career and where you plan to see yourself in the future.
You may want to be more current by bringing up some fun activity you
plan to do the next day. This may spark conversation and break the ice
between you.
The next time someone asks you to introduce yourself or to tell them a little
about yourself, consider being more fun with the answers. Don’t limit
yourself to the obvious way of introducing yourself, as there are many other
ways to break the ice with your introduction. Give them a better
understanding of who you are, and this can simply be achieved by using the
past, present, and future strategy.
Business Networking Icebreakers
Icebreakers aren’t only valuable to use in your personal life; they can also be
important in the business world. Sometimes you need to be able to break the
ice in a more professional environment. You want to find the most casual
and organic ways to break the ice at work events or on an everyday basis in
the office. These icebreakers must also be professional, so you make a good
impression in the work environment. Here are some business networking
icebreakers that can help you network effectively.
Ask for advice. If you’re trying to break the ice with someone who is
in a higher-up position, a great way to start conversations with them is
by asking them for advice in the company or industry. If they are well-
experienced, they will have great advice that helps you to further
yourself in your career. Maybe you can ask them how they got to this
high-up position, and they can provide you with valuable tips.
Give a compliment. Nothing improves the mood of the workplace
more than offering a genuine compliment. No matter what position
someone might be in your office or your industry, they will appreciate
being acknowledged and seen. If you see an intern and you want to
build a connection with someone else who is new to the company, you
can tell them they’re doing a really good job. On the other hand, if you
go to a work event and see someone really big in the industry, you can
let them know you admire their work and accomplishments.
Complimenting them can ease any awkwardness.
Tell a story. Everyone likes a good story to help break the ice in an
awkward or tense situation. When you find yourself in a work event
around lots of people and it’s awkward and silent, you can be the
courageous individual who breaks the silence by sharing a story. You
can share a work-related story that everyone can laugh at or relate to.
This may even influence other people to start sharing their work stories,
which results in a great time.
Sometimes you’ll find yourself in a position at work where you’re
surrounded by awkward silence that you have to confront. Instead of letting
the awkwardness or tension grow within your work relationships, you can
use these icebreakers to eliminate the silence. You may find that once you
utilize these strategies, work conversations begin to flow again, and those
awkward silences become a distant memory.
Casual Icebreakers
You may find yourself in a situation where you don’t want to try too hard to
break the ice, as it makes you come off desperate. It’s valuable to have
casual icebreakers that help you to break the awkwardness without trying too
hard. If you want to break away from the boring and professional norm of
starting conversations, then you should explore some more casual
icebreakers. These are some fun and interesting ways you can break the ice
in different situations.
Using Questions
A great way to break the ice casually is by asking relevant questions. If you
don’t know how to get other people to start talking in a situation, and you
want everything to be less awkward with conversation, then asking questions
is the most effective way to make the silence disappear. You need to learn
how to word questions in a way that engages conversation. Here is an
example of using questions to instigate conversation.
Say you’re with a date and you’ve run out of small talk and topics to talk
about. You’re at a romantic restaurant and you are unsure of how to break
the tension and awkwardness between you. Through this example, you can
see how the circumstances were awkward, but you saved the day casually by
asking the right questions.
You: It’s nice weather we’ve been having.
Date: Yeah, true.
You: In this type of weather I like to go swimming, especially if I’m near a
beach! Have you ever visited a place that had a beach?
Date: No, I actually never have. I’ve always lived inland, and I’ve never
done much traveling.
You: Really? I reckon that one of our future dates we should travel
somewhere close by to a beach so that you can experience it.
Date: That’s a great idea. I see you’re confident that there will be more dates
after this one, I’m glad.
In this conversation you can see how a boring small talk conversation starter
helped to save the conversation, as you used questions to further things
along. You made your date feel included, and they were interested in the
conversation as well as a date afterward.
Playing Games
If you are in more of a casual gathering or party atmosphere, then you can
play a game together to break the ice. Social gatherings can often be
awkward in the beginning, especially if the participants don’t know each
other. Playing a fun and light-hearted game helps you to get to know
everyone better, as well as breaks the ice.
People will start to feel more comfortable with each other as they laugh and
play around. This will help people to form connections, and the gathering
becomes a lot less awkward and tense. Everyone will start conversing with
each other and enjoying the event.
Starting Conversations
You really want to speak to a specific individual next to you, as you want to
get to know them, but you have no idea how to start the conversation. Being
able to start conversations with small talk is vital, as it helps you to
communicate everything you want to share. No important conversations,
bonding moments, or eye-opening conversations can occur if you don’t use
conversation starters to initiate communication with people. We will discuss
different ways you can start conversations naturally and effortlessly.
The FORD Method
One way you can use small talk to break the tension and awkwardness with
someone is by using the FORD method to come up with small talk topics.
Using small talk may be your worst nightmare because you have no idea
what topics to talk about and how to bring it up. When you use the FORD
method, it helps you to go through some general topics that will help
instigate successful and effective small talk. This is what FORD stands for
and how it can help you start a conversation:
Family: The first topic you can bring up when talking to someone is
their family. This is a pretty general and safe topic, as most people love
to talk about their family, and it makes them passionate. When you
learn about people’s families you also discover a lot about them on a
personal level, which helps you to connect with them. Some questions
you can ask regarding family can include, “Do you have siblings?”,
“Are you in a relationship?”, and “How did you two meet each other?”
Remember that family aren’t just blood relatives, as you can also ask
questions about romantic partners and friends. When talking about
family, you must be careful to not ask too many personal questions.
Occupation: The next thing you can bring up in small talk is
occupation. It’s an easy way to learn about the person you’re talking to,
as you can discover what job they have, as well as what career they’re
hoping to excel in. This is also an opportunity for you to disclose your
occupation so that they learn about what you do for a living. You could
ask them questions similar to the following: “What do you do for a
living?” and “Do you enjoy your current job?” If you’re talking to
someone who’s studying or is unemployed, you can ask the following
questions: “What are you studying?” and “What’s your dream job that
you’d like to have?” These are interesting ways to spark some
conversation.
Recreation: To get even more personal, you can ask about the person’s
recreation. This means that you learn about their hobbies and interests.
Discovering this helps you to learn about what this person enjoys doing
in their downtime. You may even find that you have similar hobbies
and interests that you can end up collaborating with. Although many
people may not realize it, we all have hobbies and interests that we
focus on in our free time, whether it’s watching television or going for
drives. You can ask the other individual questions such as, “What do
you do in your spare time?” and “Why do you enjoy doing this hobby
or interest?” Let them know your recreation activities, as they may
relate with you!
Dreams: If you want to have a more interesting and personal small talk
conversation with someone, you can find out more about their dreams
and what drives them in life. We all have personal dreams and
aspirations that drive us every day, so it’s valuable to find out this
information from people around us. When you ask people about their
dreams in life, you will see them talk with passion and happiness. This
will brighten up the conversation, as you both bond on a topic that is
dear to your hearts. When you ask what people’s dreams are, you
mustn’t be pushy to get an answer, as this is information not everyone
wants to share. You can ask questions such as the following: “Where do
you see yourself in the future?” and “What is something you hope to
achieve by the end of the year?”
These are some really safe topics to talk about that most people will always
have an answer to. We all have family, whether they’re blood-related or
important figures in our lives. Your occupation may not be something you’re
passionate about, but you most likely have dreams that you want to pursue in
your life. You have passions and interests that you practice in your free time.
Talking about any of these topics can bring out positive responses from
people, as they are the topics that often matter most.
The ARE Method
The next method you can use to start a conversation is the ARE method. If
you’ve used all the conversation starters in the previous FORD method and
you don’t know how else to continue with your small talk, you can use the
ARE method to help you initiate more conversation. This is what ARE
stands for and how it can help you pursue conversation:
Anchor: You want to start off by anchoring your conversation on a
specific topic that you will both have shared interest in. It’s best to
bring up a topic that you are mutually experiencing at the moment. For
example, you can bring up something about the environment or
atmosphere you’re in. This way you both have something to say about
the topic, as you’re both experiencing it. If you are in a wedding
reception and you’re waiting in a line for food, you can talk to the
person next to you and say something like, “The food looks and smells
absolutely amazing.”
Reveal: After you use an anchor to start a conversation, you must
continue to reveal something about yourself. You can’t just leave the
conversation at the anchor; otherwise it will go quiet and awkward
again. When you reveal something about yourself, it makes the
conversation more personal and interesting. You can say something
like, “Lasagna is my favorite meal, but I haven’t been able to eat it
because I was on a strict diet,” with a small laugh. Disclosing
something light-hearted about yourself can influence the person you’re
conversing with to engage in small talk with you.
Encourage: Once you’ve done your job of starting the conversation
and revealing something about yourself, you need to be able to
encourage them to talk next. It’s a successful small talk session if both
parties are talking to each other casually. If the other individual hasn’t
spoken yet, you must take the opportunity to ask them questions to
encourage them to get involved in the conversation. For example, you
can ask them, “What is your favorite food here?” Basic and simple
questions can help instigate conversation, as you make them feel more
included.
The ARE method is a great way to get small talk started, as it covers all of
the important bases. You bring up a topic and anchor the conversation,
which signifies you breaking the silence. You then talk about yourself by
revealing something related to the topic, and from there, you’re able to
encourage the other person to talk, too. This results in balanced small talk
where both parties get to talk about themselves.
Topics of Discussion
There are many other casual and organic ways you can start conversation
with any type of person. Here are some concrete examples of how you can
use everyday topics and observations to start conversing with others. If
you’re not great at starting conversations with people, it’s valuable to
prepare yourself with topics of discussions you can use for different
scenarios and situations.
Safe, Universal Topics
If you ever find yourself in a sticky situation where you feel awkward and
speechless, but you really want to communicate with the other person, it’s
valuable to have some safe universal topics to turn to. It’s like a safety net to
have some universal topics that you utilize in any situation, as this can help
you start a conversation in any scenario. Here are some universal topics you
can bring up to almost anyone at any given time:
Did anything exciting happen to you today?
What makes you happy in your everyday life?
What was the last great movie you watched?
What type of music do you listen to?
What do you enjoy doing in your downtime?
What do you do to relax and decompress?
All these types of topics are safe, as they question general things about other
people. You don’t always need to ask such personal questions to people,
especially if you’re not close with them already. Start off small by asking
these universal conversation starters, and from there give the conversation
space to develop.
Topics for Friends
If you find yourself in a dry spell with your friends as you struggle to find
ways to start a conversation, there are certain topics that can make your
communication more interesting. Whether you’re trying to start a
conversation with a friend you’ve known for a long time, a new
acquaintance, or a stranger you’re trying to get close to, these topics will
help you to break down that barrier and connect with each other.
Blast from the past: If this is a friend from your past that you’re
reuniting with, it can be awkward. You’ve both changed so much, and
you have no idea how to approach the conversation with this “stranger.”
You must remember that they actually aren’t strangers, as you have
countless memories with them. These memories are valuable, as they
can be used as conversation starters. You can bring up fun times you
had together in the past to lighten the mood and show your friend that
it’s valuable to try and reconnect with each other.
Common interests: If you’re trying to make a new friend, the best way
to do this is by communicating some common interests. It’s always
awkward meeting someone for the first time and trying to make friends
with them, unless you just click instantly. If you don’t click with this
new potential friend, it’s best to find some common interests that you
can relate to each other with. By using different small talk methods
such as ARE and FORD, you can learn more about each other and what
makes you similar.
Friendship topics: If you’re looking for more broad conversation
topics to pique your friends’ interest, then you should consider using
some basic topics such as, “What have you been doing in your free
time?” and “How has your week been so far?” Asking these questions
helps you to learn about what your friend has been doing in their
downtime. This gives you something to talk about, as you discover
what they spend their time doing; you also learn what activities you can
do together to make them happy.
Topics for Business
Striving to excel in your industry means that you need to be able to think
quickly on your toes. The business world requires you to be a conservator at
times so that you can connect with people and network successfully. When
you want to have some standard topics for your business and professional
life, you need to be able to come up with ones that are applicable for you.
You need to think of topics that are relative and applicable to your industry
and line of work, as this will make them more valuable and effective.
Consider what types of topics are brought up frequently in the office by your
boss and colleagues. Understanding what’s common to talk about in your
professional life will help you to come up with a set of business topics that
you can use when you find yourself in an awkward position at work.
Topics to Avoid
As there are topics that are suitable for most situations, there are also some
topics that are important to avoid. You don’t want to find yourself bringing
up conversation topics that make the environment more awkward and silent.
You must be able to read the room and know when it’s the time and place for
certain topics. Conversation starters are meant to be safe, so that they make
the other person feel more comfortable to openly talk to you. These are some
topics you must avoid altogether when you are trying to begin conversation.
Gossiping: No good conversation occurs when you start it off with
unnecessary gossip. Although gossip may shock and entice the people
around you, it’s not the best way to make a first impression on
someone. You should avoid saying low blows or judging other people
to break the silence in the room. You may think using gossip is a great
strategy to start a conversation, but more often than less it’ll end up
negatively impacting you in the long run. You don’t want people to
perceive you as a judgmental individual who gossips behind other
people’s backs.
Controversial topics: The next thing you must avoid doing when you
are starting conversations is bring up controversial topics. Everyone has
their own opinions in life, and you never know how strongly someone
believes in something. You may bring up a controversial topic, such as
religion and politics, which gets a strong reaction out of the person
you’re talking to. You could end up disagreeing and ultimately fighting
with each other.
Personal finance: Another area that is inappropriate to ask another
person is about their personal finances. We can all get curious at times
about what other people make for a living, but you must never indulge
in your curiosity by asking them about what they make. When people
are asked how much they make, they usually feel uncomfortable and
put on the spot. If you want to boast about how much you make or you
want to open up about your deep financial issues, it’s best to keep this
to yourself. This isn’t something you should be talking about to start a
conversation, as it won’t influence better communication.
Family and relationship issues: If someone is experiencing problems
in the relationships in their life, it’s not your job to bring it up. You may
know someone is going through some relationship problems in their life
and you feel curious to know, so that you can help them. If they would
like to talk to you about their personal issues, then let them come to you
first with the problems. Bringing up personal issues can start off a
conversation on a bad note, which makes the other individual
disinterested in pursuing small talk.
Using Daily Observations
With all of these scenarios and situations, you can learn how to create topics
of discussion by just utilizing daily observations around you. You don’t
always have to use stock topics to start conversations, as you can make a
conversation out of any observation that’s currently occurring around you.
These are some everyday observations that can help you to instigate
conversations:
What objects are around you? We are constantly surrounded by objects
in our everyday life, but did you know that these objects can act as
effective conversation starters? Sometimes all you need to do when
you’re stuck in a conversation is observe what objects are around you
and determine how they can be turned into conversation.
What’s occurring around you? You can then take a look at the events
happening around you. Are there any interesting events or activities
happening in your surroundings? Bringing up something that you’re
mutually witnessing or experiencing together is a great opportunity to
bond and conversate. It’s easier to bring up small talk in a situation you
can both go through in the current moment.
What type of day is it for the other person? We all know one of the
most common small talk topics is about the weather, but let’s be honest,
this topic is very outdated. When anyone brings up the weather, it’s
common knowledge that they’re engaging in small talk. When you ask
yourself what type of day it is, think to yourself what may make this
day more distinctive or interesting to the other person. You may
discover that they have a big pitch that day or they are going on a date
with someone. Talking about these topics will pique the other person’s
interest, because who doesn’t like talking about themselves?
CHAPTER 3
How to Carry a Conversation
"Let the conversation flow at its own pace, don't try to rush it or control it.
You need to let go and be part of the conversation." – Max Weiss
Your number one priority should be to use small talk to carry the
conversation. Unfortunately, you can’t guarantee that every person you talk
to is charismatic and able to carry a conversation. You may be talking to
someone who is shyer and more introverted, which means they struggle to
instigate conversation. This is where you come in, as you can use small talk
to carry conversation.
You may be thinking to yourself that you’re not someone who can carry a
conversation, as you are shy, less talkative, and awkward when the attention
is on you. It’s important to realize that being able to carry conversation is
easy and achievable for any individual, as long as you utilize your
confidence, take control of the conversation, and use your tips and tricks for
small talk to keep the conversation going.
How to Keep the Conversation Flowing
You may become a master at starting conversations with small talk, but as
the time passes, things begin to get awkward again. Many people struggle
to continue keeping a conversation flowing for long, especially if they’re
not getting a lot of feedback from the person they’re talking to. Being able
to know how to keep a conversation flowing can alleviate that awkward
silence you get from the conversation slowly dying.
Never Running Out of Things to Say
Most wish we could have an endless number of topics to talk about so that
we can never experience awkward silence in a conversation. In the
beginning of a conversation, you feel confident and filled with ideas and
topics to talk about, but as time passes, your conversation begins to
dwindle. Did you know that you can prevent yourself from running out of
things to say? Here are some ideas you can use to ensure that you never run
out of conversation:
1. Consider what you’re thinking. We all experience thousands of
thoughts in a day, and although some of them may be silly or stupid,
some of your thoughts could be valuable or effective conversation
topics. We often just come up with topics based on what we are
experiencing around us, but why not bring up a random topic off the
top of your head? You may be surprised with the fun and interesting
topics you come up with.
2. Look around you. If your brain is completely blank and you don’t
have any interesting thoughts, then you may want to try and take a
look at your surroundings. There’s so many conversation starters
around us that we don’t even realize sometimes. Take a look at the
room you’re in now and consider all the different objects you’re
surrounded by. Maybe you can see that there are four empty used mugs
in your room that you used to drink coffee. This can be a conversation
starter, as you tell the other person that you have a coffee addiction
because you drink four cups every day. Something as small and basic
as a few mugs can turn into a whole topic of conversation.
3. Talk about your interests. Coming up with new topics is as easy as
looking internally and considering what you are interested in.
Sometimes bringing anything up with some passion and zest helps the
conversation to start flowing again. You can even go back to previous
topics that were spoken about and add onto them. There are no set
rules to coming up with topics, so you must have fun with it and talk
about what interests you. When you talk about what fascinates and
excites you, you will end up sparking interest in the person that you’re
talking to.
4. Don’t be so desperate. Although it’s vital to make a proper effort
when coming up with new topics, you must avoid coming off too
desperate. Nobody likes to try hard to force conversation with things
that get awkward. If the conversation has run its course and there’s
nothing else to talk about, then you shouldn’t be afraid to end it there.
Say your pleasantries and move on with your day. You also don’t want
to force more conversation with someone when you can see that they
are beginning to get disinterested, so you must know when it’s time to
stop talking.
At the end of the day, you don’t have to think of the most interesting topics
to talk about. You just need to be able to present these topics with
excitement, as your delivery makes a big impact on how well your
conversations will flow. You will be surprised to find out how many
different topics you can think of by being creative. Let your mind go wild
and don’t be afraid to bring up new topics.
Using Storytelling
As stated earlier, using stories in conversation is a great way to pique
interest. If you find that conversation is beginning to dry out and you’re
unsure how to revive the conversation, then you should try telling stories.
Let’s be honest, a good story has the power to captivate your attention. You
can see this when you watch an interesting movie or television show. As
humans, we’re easily entertained by stories, but we can often forget how to
utilize storytelling in our day-to-day lives. If you want to reignite the spark
and intrigue in your conversation, then telling a juicy and interesting story
is a great way to achieve this. This is how you can utilize storytelling to
keep the conversation flowing:
Think of relevant stories. We live and create stories each day we live,
so it’s not difficult to think of a good story for different situations.
When you find yourself in a quiet or awkward position in a
conversation, take some time to think of an interesting story to tell.
You should use your environment and current situation or topic of
interest to bring up a story that’s relative to your mutual, current
reality.
Spice it up. When you’re thinking of a story to captivate the interest of
the person you’re talking to, you need to have a balance of reality and
spice. Sometimes the cold hard facts of a story can be a little plain and
boring, so there’s nothing wrong with spicing it up a little bit, as long
as it’s not harming anyone and you’re not lying about a situation.
Spicing it up means that you use interesting phrases and details to
enhance the experience of hearing this story. You must avoid
fabricating a whole story, as you may find yourself caught in a lie, and
nothing makes a conversation more awkward than being caught lying.
Leave room for other people to share. Because you’re using
storytelling with the purpose to keep conversation going, you need to
leave room for other people to talk and share. You want your story to
be a conversation starter, so it’s important to welcome other people
speaking, as well as other individuals sharing their own stories. This
will help to continue the conversation and alleviate any awkwardness.
You can even encourage them to share their own stories by asking if
they have any fun interesting stories that are similar.
Taking Control of the Conversation
There’s always that one person who's able to take command of a room.
They know exactly how to start the conversation and ensure that it never
becomes dry. Learning how to become this individual who knows exactly
how to take control of a conversation and keep it flowing is extremely
valuable. If you’re in control of the conversation, you don’t have to worry
about things getting awkward or tense. These are some valuable and
effective tips that will help you to take control of any conversation you’re
in:
Speak with clarity. The biggest thing to take note of when you’re
trying to make a conversation flow successfully is that you need to
speak and communicate with clarity. How you choose to say your
words and what you actually say have an impact on how well your
communication is perceived. You need to make sure that you are
verbally expressing yourself with clarity so that people can hear every
single word you say. Not only must you physically speak with clarity,
but you must also ensure the content of your words are clear. Try to get
to the point when you talk, so that people can hear that you know
exactly what you’re talking about.
Talk with confidence. Being in control of a conversation means that
you talk with confidence. No one is going to let you guide them in a
conversation when you speak softly, with very little conviction. You
want to make an impact on the people you’re talking to so that they
can see you’re the one in charge in the conversation. Talking with
confidence essentially means that you believe in what you’re saying.
Don’t doubt yourself or be afraid of embarrassing yourself, but rather
speak with conviction and assurance.
Steer the conversation. If you want to have control of the
conversation, you may want to manipulate and steer it in a way that’s
suitable for you. You may have a specific agenda when speaking to
someone, as you want to cover a specific topic. To do this, you need to
successfully take control of the conversation. This means that you can
steer the topic to what you would rather talk about. When you steer the
conversation to a new topic, you need to be able to do it organically,
instead of forcing the conversation topic to change. You can also use
this tactic of steering conversation when you’re talking about a topic
you’re not entirely comfortable with.
Asking Questions
When in doubt during a conversation, ask questions. If you’re feeling lost
and stuck in a conversation, the cheat code is to ask the other person
questions. You may find that the conversation isn’t going anywhere because
the other person isn’t giving you much feedback as you talk. No matter
what you say or bring up, they don’t get entirely involved in the small talk.
Using questions is the best way to include someone and get the
conversation flowing properly. These are some reasons why asking
questions is valuable to keep the conversation going.
Encouraging Others to Talk
You may think that you’re not the type of person who likes to talk often,
especially when it’s about yourself. You’re fearful that you will bore the
other person and talk their ear off. Have you ever considered that other
individuals feel the same way when they talk to you? You may be talking to
someone who feels shy to talk about themselves, which causes the
conversation to become stagnant.
However, when you end up asking them questions about themselves, it
encourages them to start talking about themselves. They can notice that
you’re interested in what they have to say, which makes them excited to
talk more about themselves. This is beneficial for your conversation in
numerous ways.
Firstly, them talking about themselves helps make the conversation flow
smoother, as it’s not just you droning on about yourself. The other person
can feel more engaged in the conversation, as they feel as though they’re
being heard equally. Asking the other person questions also helps you think
of more topics to think about. It can be stressful carrying a conversation, as
you constantly feel as though you need to think of interesting, new topics.
When the person you’re talking to answers questions, you get more inspired
to think of more topics of discussion, and conversation runs easily.
Making the Other Person Feel Important
Asking relevant and appropriate questions has the power to make people
feel more important and heard. In life, we’re all so focused on ourselves
that it can cause us to act self-absorbed, and focus less on the people around
us. When you take the effort to genuinely ask other people questions, it
makes them feel like they are important and you want to hear about them.
If you want to use communication to improve your relationships or build
connections, then asking them questions is the perfect way to achieve this.
You make the other person feel like their words have value and meaning,
which elevates the experience of small talk. It’s more than just having
general conversation, as they feel like their opinions and thoughts are truly
being heard.
Examples of Suitable Questions
You may be wondering what type of questions you should ask to get the
conversation ball rolling. There are some positive and effective questions
that you can ask the other person, but there are also questions that you must
try to avoid altogether. It’s valuable to know what types of questions are
suitable to ask to get the conversation flowing. These are merely a few
examples of suitable questions that can instigate more conversation:
What do you think about this situation? This question is valuable to
get an opinion out of someone. If you want the other person to give
their input, you can ask this question to hear their point of view. They
will feel like their perspective is cared about. Hearing their opinion
also helps to instigate conversation, as you can give your perspective,
which influences healthy discussion.
How would you react in my position? If you find yourself talking
about yourself a lot and a situation you’re experiencing, it’s valuable to
get them involved by asking a simple question. Asking someone what
they would do in your situation forces them to put themselves in your
shoes. They begin to feel more included and feel as though the
conversation isn’t just about you.
Where did you get that amazing outfit? Complimenting someone in
the form of a question goes a long way. Merely telling someone they
look good or you like their outfit will make the other person feel
happy, but asking them where they got their outfit from gives them the
impression that you truly care about their outfit and where it’s from.
What happened with that crazy customer you were dealing with?
Bringing up a story from the past is a great way to alleviate any
awkwardness or tension. When you bring up a funny or interesting
situation that the other person has been through, they can have
something to talk to you about. Also, remembering something they
told you in the past and bringing it up shows them that you truly listen
to them.
These are all thought-provoking questions that can help anyone feel more
involved in a conversation. Remember that you can’t keep a conversation
going on your own, as it takes two people to have successful small talk.
Using questions is vital, as it’s the only surefire way to get other people
involved and engaged. These question examples may seem small and
meaningless, but they can really instigate great small talk that makes both
parties feel included.
CHAPTER 4
Principles for Success to Captivate
Listeners
" A real conversation always contains an invitation. You are inviting
another person to reveal herself or himself to you, to tell you who they are
or what they want." – David Whyte
Small talk is tricky to tackle, as you can either be interesting and influence
engagement, or you may end up boring the other person. Let’s face it,
talking about the weather and how warm it is isn’t the most riveting
conversation topic. You want to ensure that your small talk is something
that other people want to actually listen to and engage with, so it’s
important to learn the following principles that will help you to captivate
the people you use small talk with.
Principles of Success for Small Talk
It can be challenging to always captivate the interest of your listeners,
especially when you’re talking about something they’re not particularly
interested in. It’s important to know how you can captivate people through
conversation, no matter what topic you’re talking about. You don’t want to
be known as the individual that bores the living daylights out of people.
You may be thinking to yourself how you can captivate people if you’re
talking about something that’s not particularly interesting. You may have a
monotonous voice or tone that doesn’t really captivate the intrigue of
listeners. This is where the principles of successful small talk come in
handy, as they can help you to captivate any listener. You must consider the
following principles as they can give you a successful small talk
experience.
Consider Who You’re Talking To
The first principle you must consider when you’re creating small talk is that
you need to take note of the individual you’re talking to. To engage in
successful small talk, it’s valuable to know a bit about your listeners.
Knowing and understanding them can make it easier for you to bring up
topics and use conversational styles that are most suitable for this type of
person.
For example, if you know the person you’re talking to is passionate about
football, and you watched the game last night, it’s a perfect opportunity to
bring it up and talk about it. This will have this person engaged and
captivated, as it’s a topic they’re really passionate about. You must also
consider how to bring up small talk to a person based on what their
personality is like. If they’re more introverted and shyer, you must be
prepared to carry the conversation and ask them questions to make them
feel included. However, if they’re outspoken and over the top, you can
match their energy to get them excited and captivated.
If you find yourself using small talk with an individual you’ve never met
before, don’t despair, as you can still find out some valuable information
about them. You should start off the conversation by asking some
informative questions that can tell you a lot about them. For example, ask
about their occupation, interests, and family situation. The more you learn
about them through general small talk, the easier you will find it to cater to
them throughout the conversation so they can be captivated.
Be Interactive
A conversation is not a one-man show, so it’s important for you to be
interactive when you’re talking to someone. If you’re not great at small talk
and you’re utilizing all the tips you’ve learnt throughout this book, you may
find that you’re so focused on how well you’re talking that you completely
ignore how the other individual is interacting with you. To ensure that
you’re being interactive, you should follow these steps:
1. Check the engagement of the listener. You need to start off by
considering how engaged your listener is. Are they intrigued by what
you have to say and are they listening properly, or can you see their
interest dwindling, as they get distracted while you speak? If you can
see the listener is captivated and engaged, then keep doing what you’re
doing, but if you can tell they aren’t interested, then it’s time to follow
the next steps to captivate them effectively.
2. Make it about them. Although none of us like to admit it, we love it
when we’re the topic of discussion. When someone goes out of their
way to talk about you specifically, you know that it gives you a good
feeling. Not only does it make you feel good, but it also makes you
more interested in listening to what’s being said. You must find ways
to involve this other person into your topic. For example, if you’re
talking about how you find big eyes really beautiful, you can involve
the person you’re talking to by saying they have amazing, big eyes that
prove your point. Trust me, this will keep them captivated in anything
you have to say afterward!
3. Ask questions, questions, and more questions. I’m sure you know
by now that questions are a valuable tool in verbal interactions. If you
want to keep the listener captivated, you can change the topic from
them to what you initially wanted to talk about. When you do this, you
may lose some of their focus, so you must introduce some questions
into the conversation to ensure they interact with you. Ask them
interesting questions that take some thought, so they actually listen to
what you have to say next.
Speak With Emotion
There’s nothing more annoying than listening to someone who sounds like
they aren’t even interested in what they’re talking about. When we hear
people talking in monotonous and boring tones, it makes it more difficult
for us to focus. A great example that proves this is within the school
environment. Think back to a teacher who used to talk slowly, with no
emotion or care for their job. You probably learnt absolutely nothing from
them.
People are more inclined to listen to people who speak with emotion and
passion, and this can be proven through our own listening. You probably
listen more attentively to people who speak with emotions, as well as
remember what they said, because their delivery made an impact on you.
You need to first be able to determine whether you’re an expressive or
emotional talker. You may think that you’re speaking with emotion because
you feel the emotions internally as you talk, but in reality you are using
little to no expressions, as well as a monotonous tone. To determine how
you communicate, you must be mindful and aware during conversations.
You can also ask people to give you an honest opinion of how you speak, as
they will know whether you use emotion when you speak or not.
If you find that you are more emotionless and expressionless when you
speak, it’s time to change that, so your conversations can be more
interesting and intriguing to others. You need to find that perfect balance of
emotion and expression when you speak, because you want to avoid being
too animated and over the top. You don’t want people to think that you’re
being fake as you speak. All you need to do is the following:
Be more mindful when you speak.
Use more facial expressions.
Have a suitable tone for the topic you’re talking about.
Have fun with it.
If you do these four things as you converse with people, you will be
guaranteed successful small talk. Above all, you must enjoy talking,
because this will ultimately result in the other person enjoying listening to
you!
How to Captivate Through Dialogue
Once you have a grasp of the principles of successful small talk, it’s
important to apply them to your conversations. It’s easy to tell yourself to
just talk with emotion or involve the other person, but you need to find
practical ways to integrate these principles into your dialogue. Below are
some examples of how you can integrate these successful small talk
principles into valuable and meaningful dialogue.
Example 1 - Knowing Who You’re Talking To
You’re having a casual conversation with your boss and you’re engaging in
small talk, but you have a hidden agenda and goal for the conversation.
You’re trying to get on your boss's good side because you made a big
mistake that you’re afraid to tell them about. Within this conversation, your
goal is to get him happy and calm before you break the news to him.
You: Hi, sir. How was your weekend?
Boss: It was okay, but I was working all weekend. While you guys get to
have a break, I’m busy working overtime.
You: I’m so sorry about that, sir. It sounds like you’re in need of a holiday.
Boss: I definitely am! I’ve been planning a trip with my wife; we love doing
outdoor activities.
You: Really, so do my wife and I. We actually went on a skiing trip last
holiday season. What kind of trips do you and your wife go on?
Boss: You name it, we’ve done it: tropical, skiing, hiking, and water
activities. We’re honestly always searching for an exciting new activity to
do together.
You: That sounds great! I’ll keep my eyes peeled for you. If I hear of a new
holiday activity, you’ll be the first to know!
Boss (chuckles): That’s very nice of you, thank you.
You: Before you go, sir, I wanted to talk to you about an error I made with
the latest documents. I need them back quickly so I can fix a silly error.
Boss: Oh, dear, I told you that you have to be more vigilant. But it’s okay.
Thank you for letting me know before I sent the documents out. Come into
my office, we’ll sort this out now.
In this example, you can see how to successfully use small talk to make
someone feel calm and comfortable talking to you. In this example, you
needed to tell your boss something serious that you were scared of
disclosing, so you found a common interest to talk about. You utilized the
principle of knowing who you’re talking to. You’re aware that your boss
loves going on holiday, traveling, and most of all, his wife. You related to
him, and this put him in a better mood. Although he may have been upset
about your mistake, he didn’t blow up in anger like he usually does,
because you calmed him down with small talk!
Example 2 - Using Emotions
You’re talking to an acquaintance you want to turn into a friend. You enjoy
the company of this individual, as she makes you laugh and she’s a really
pure individual. However, whenever you try to make conversation with her
it becomes awkward, as she doesn’t seem particularly interested in speaking
to you. You find out that it’s your monotonous speaking that makes it hard
to captivate her attention, as she’s always busy with something to do.
You: Rebecca, is that you?
Rebecca: Hi, yes…I’m sorry, I can’t remember where I know you from.
You (laughs): No offense taken! Honestly, this is such a wild coincidence!
We met a few months ago at our daughters’ school. It’s funny because my
little girl was literally talking about your daughter and saying how much
they’re getting along!
Rebecca: Wow! Really? That makes me so happy, because my little one is a
bit socially awkward.
You: I can relate to her because I’m a bit socially awkward, too, if you can’t
tell already. And trust me, I turned out fine! I like to think, at least – haha.
Rebecca (laughs): You seem great!. Maybe we should go for coffee
sometime, or arrange a playdate for our kids.
You: That honestly sounds great! Let me give you my number so we can set
a date.
In this example, you can see how you turned a total stranger or
acquaintance into a potential friend. It can be scary to make the first step,
but you’ll be surprised how well it turns out, especially when you approach
the other person with the right energy. For this instance, you brought up
something in common you two have, which is daughters who go to the
same school. You used their budding friendship as an opportunity to
captivate Rebecca’s attention. Using expressive words, like “Wow,” making
jokes, and speaking in an upbeat tone successfully got the other person’s
attention and interest.
Example 3 - Mutual Interaction
You’re on a date with someone you’ve been seeing for a few weeks now.
You really like him, but you feel like he’s not as interested in you because
he barely talks. You can see that he is more of an introverted individual,
while you’re outgoing and extroverted. You end up talking the whole date,
while he just sits there looking spaced out. You need to find a way to get
him interacting.
You: So I told my boss straight that I cannot continue working overtime
every day, while I’m still getting unpaid. It’s honestly ridiculous what I had
to go through…but enough about me. I feel like I’ve just been blabbing
about myself the whole time. Do you have a good relationship with your
boss?
Date: Not really, he’s not the nicest person to be around.
You: Really? What do you mean by that?
Date: He’s very uptight and wants everything done his way. If you’re
working around him, you must be prepared to be absolutely micromanaged.
You: That’s awful! Would you say you’re an overachiever, or do you just go
to work to get the bare minimum done, like me?
Date: Honestly, I’d say I’m a bit of both. Sometimes I enjoy overachieving
because I’m passionate about my work, but my boss makes it difficult for
me to grow or flourish. I end up going to work just doing the bare minimum,
instead of giving him my all.
You: I completely understand what you mean. I’d love to hear more about
your work; it honestly sounds really interesting.
This conversation is a perfect example of how you can make a quieter
person open up to you more. You need to avoid letting yourself steal the
spotlight, so you can give the other person the time and space to talk. By
asking your date appropriate questions, you’re able to hear more about him
and his work life. He also felt more listened to, which made him enjoy the
date more. At the end of the day, we all like to feel heard by someone, and
that’s what makes both parties engaging in small talk feel captivated and
interested in each other.
CHAPTER 5
Creating an Emotional Connection
"Ultimately the bond of all companionship, whether in marriage or in
friendship, is conversation." – Oscar Wilde
Using small talk is not just to break the ice and make things less awkward;
it can also be used to build emotional connections with other people. In life,
you want to build stronger connections, build new relationships, and make
good impressions on the people you meet for the first time. How you plan
on utilizing your small talk can establish how successfully you create
emotional connections with people.
Many individuals have a misconception that small talk is shallow and
surface-level, but the topics you touch on during small talk can cover really
important issues to both you and the person you’re talking to. Small talk
can instigate deep and meaningful connections that help you to create
emotional connections. It’s also a valuable tool to get closer to people, as
the more small talk you use, the more comfortable you get with each other.
Why Build Emotional Connections With Small
Talk?
You may be wondering why you need to use your small talking skills to
build emotional connections in your life, but we don’t realize how
beneficial those connections can be. Meeting new people and creating
bonds can create so much value in your life that you don’t even realize. You
never know how much value someone can bring into your life just by
emotionally connecting with them.
Whether we like to admit it or not, we all need emotional connections in our
life. Getting close to others and forming bonds with the people in our lives
can bring us more value and meaning in our everyday life. We tend to forget
the value of an emotional connection and how it can be created through
simple and easy strategies.
When you use small talk to build connections with others, you’ll find it
easier to make friendships and build bonds. We often assume that the best
way to build a connection with someone is by going through a special
experience together, or by opening up to each other emotionally, but how do
you get to this phase of a relationship? It all begins with small talk, so you
need to be mindful as to how you use your small talk to create lifelong
bonds!
Building Deeper Connections
When you think of small talk, you probably think of it as superficial
discussions that don’t do anything to help you in terms of building and
growing your relationships. You may even think it does the opposite of
building connections, as it can be awkward at times. However, when small
talk is practiced effectively, it enables you to build strong connections you
didn’t know were possible.
Building Rapport
One of the best ways to build a connection with someone through the use of
small talk is by building rapport with them. Building rapport with someone
essentially means that you grow close to someone and form a mutual,
meaningful relationship with them. It’s a bond that is formed between two
people who realize they have things in common and they click on a deeper
level. These are some tips that will make it easier for you to build rapport:
Know the basics. When it comes to building rapport, you need to
make sure you’re taking care of the basics of building connections.
You need to ensure that you’re creating the best circumstances to
create a bond. For example, you need to show that you’re a
trustworthy individual that can be caring and nonjudgmental. If the
circumstances are right, they will feel more open to forming a
relationship with you. Some of the basics that are important to
consider include smiling, being culturally appropriate, and speaking
with confidence.
Be empathetic. One of the best ways to build rapport with someone is
by being empathetic to them. In life, we all just want to be heard and
understood, which means that we want someone to feel empathetic and
caring toward us, especially when we’re going through negative
circumstances. You need to ensure that you’re empathetic to others,
especially when they are going through something negative. If
someone is opening up to you about something bad in their life, you
should respond in a way that shows your empathy and care toward
them.
Mirror. One technique that can be proven effective to building rapport
is mirroring the person you’re talking to. Did you know that mirroring
and matching other people’s body language gives them a perception
that you are both alike? When you copy the other person’s hand
gestures, mannerisms, and facial expressions, they will subconsciously
think that you are similar to them. This makes it easier for people to
get closer to you, as they already think you have common ground.
There are different levels to rapport, so you can’t expect to be extremely
close with someone right away. It’ll take time to build deeper rapport with
individuals in your life, so you can’t force or rush the process. Using these
previous tips in an organic and casual manner will help you to build
genuine rapport that will grow and adapt with time.
Signs You’re Building a Connection
Do you have a sense of awareness when it comes to building connections?
Are you able to recognize when a connection is being formed and someone
is warming up to you? It’s not only important to know how to build these
emotional connections with small talk, but it’s also important to discover
when you’re successfully building connections with it.
Knowing whether you’re successfully building connections helps you to
continue what you’re doing, and if you notice you’re not quite getting there,
you can improve your strategy.
One sign that you’re beginning to build and develop a connection with
someone is that you begin to share openly between each other. When you
don’t have a bond or emotional connection with someone, you will find it
challenging to tell them things that are personal to you. If you find yourself
opening up easily and freely to this person, it’s a sign that you have a
deeper bond and connection. You feel comfortable telling them personal
matters that are meaningful and deep to you, and they are able to do the
same thing in return.
You’re interested in each other's passions. Building an emotional
connection with someone means that you get fascinated or intrigued by
what the other person is interested in. Although they may have a passion
you don’t share, when you hear them talk about it with conviction, it sparks
your interest. You find yourself having small talk over their interests, even
though they may have had no relevance to you in your past. You may even
participate in these activities together, as you know it means a lot to them.
The other person also makes the same effort for your own passions and
interests.
How you listen to someone shows how deep a connection may be. When
you talk to an acquaintance, you listen to them briefly, but you don’t
properly take in everything they have to say. When you find yourself
listening attentively to what another person has to say and you genuinely
care for them, it’s a sign that you’re building a connection. You listen to
them with empathy, without judging their actions or the circumstances.
When you notice someone else listens to you attentively and shows real
concern or empathy, this shows that they are building an emotional bond
with you.
It’s all about being able to read the room and identify when you’re winning
someone over. You can also tell through body language, verbal cues, and
the tone in which someone is talking. All of these indicators can show you
when someone is feeling closer to you or not. Your ultimate goal should be
to make the other individual feel comfortable to open up and let their guard
down with you. So if you can see the other person is tense, wants to walk
away, and responds with a maximum of two words, it may be a sign that
you need to let go of trying to force an emotional connection.
How to Make People Like You
At the end of the day, all we want as humans is to be liked by the people in
our life and by the new strangers we meet every day. You want to be able to
make a good first impression on people and win them over, so to speak. It’s
challenging to know how to make people like you through small talk,
because you don’t want to come off too desperate, but at the same time you
want to make a good effort that is recognized.
Cialdini’s Principles of Persuasion
Robert Cialdini is a psychologist who published a book called Influence:
The Psychology of Persuasion. His philosophy centered around decision
making, as he explored all the aspects that influence people to make
decisions in their lives. Although these principles are focused on
influencing people in sales, it can be applied to socializing with others. You
can use these principles to influence how people perceive you so that you
can increase your chances of forming deeper connections. These are
Cialdini’s six principles of persuasion and how they can help you:
1. Reciprocity: In life, we don’t like to feel indebted to others, as it can
feel like a burden. We all like to feel equality. If you do something nice
and caring for the people in your lives, chances are they will want to
do something in return, to uphold this balance. You’ll end up doing
nice things for each other, which builds a connection over time.
2. Scarcity: This principle states that the less of something there is, the
more in demand it gets. People like things that are scarce and not
available to everyone. This makes it valuable for you to be selective
when you choose who to make friends with. When people can see that
you’re selective and picky with the people you choose to create bonds
with, it makes them more intrigued by you. They also feel flattered
that you chose them.
3. Authority: People with authority are naturally more persuasive and
influential, which makes it easier for them to be liked by others.
Believe it or not, but we like individuals who are direct, strong, and act
with authority. You feel a sense of trust toward them because it appears
that they know what they’re talking about. If you are confident with
how you approach people and speak with authority and respect, people
