will warm up to you.
4. Consistency and commitment: If you want to win people over in life,
make them like you, and build emotional connections with them, it
takes more than being nice to them as you approach them. You need to
be consistent with your efforts and show that you’re a valuable person
to have in their life. Being a good friend, partner, or colleague, who is
consistent with their positive behavior, will help you create reliable
and long lasting bonds.
5. Liking: When you’re trying to be more liked by others, you need to
consider this principle. The art of being persuasive and influential is
only effective when you’re liked as an individual. People aren’t going
to be influenced by you if they don’t like you as a person. This is why
it’s important to be a likable person, while still being true to your
nature. You can merely work on being friendly, to increase your
likeability.
6. Social proof: As people, we are influenced by social proof. We are
more likely to be influential and persuasive when there’s social
evidence of it. If people see that you are liked by others, they are more
likely to let you into their lives, as they see that you are a friendly
individual who has some sense of social status.
Tips to Make Other People Like You
Before getting into tips that can make people like you, it’s important to
realize that people’s approval doesn’t matter. Although we all want to be
liked and appreciated by others, we shouldn’t value their opinions over our
own. We can often get carried away with trying to impress other people that
it causes us to stop being true to ourselves. At the end of the day, you don’t
want to appear desperate for other people’s approval. These are some tips
that will help you get liked by others in a healthy manner:
Be yourself. The first thing you must consider when you’re trying to
be liked by others is whether you’re being true to yourself. It’s crucial
to never prioritize being approved by others over your true nature.
Believe it or not, but being yourself can actually make people like you
more. Nobody wants to be friends with someone perfect who’s always
trying hard, as they would rather build a connection with someone who
has a real personality. When you fully embrace your personality, you
attract the right people into your life who will like you for being
yourself.
Be personal. Don’t be afraid to make the conversation personal to the
other person. The only way to truly build connections and get close to
other people is by having the personal conversations that help you to
connect on a deeper level. You need to show that you’re a safe space
for someone to open up to. You can make a conversation personal by
initially sharing personal things about yourself first. When you open
up to them in confidence, it shows them that you’re also a safe space to
open up to. You will find that you get into a deeper conversation,
where you comfort each other and strengthen your bond.
Be friendly. Friendliness goes a long way. When you’re trying to build
connections with people, instead of trying to be the person you think
they want you to be, you must be yourself and embrace friendliness.
People are more likely to get closer to you if they can see that you’re a
friendly, caring, and nonjudgmental individual. There are some very
simple and straightforward ways to appear more friendly to people.
You can smile more as you speak, be comforting when necessary,
remember the person’s name and details about them, and make light-
hearted jokes when it’s suitable. Doing these small things will give
other people the impression that you’re friendly and easy to talk to.
Examples of Building Connections
Now that you know how to build emotional connections, it’s valuable to
look at practical ways you can integrate these skills and tips into your
everyday small talk. You want to be able to work on building connections in
a natural and organic way, so it’s important to know how to use small talk to
build connections. You don’t want to appear too forced or disingenuous;
these examples will help you integrate the previous tips and tricks into your
everyday dialogue seamlessly.
Example 1 - Being Empathetic
When you’re building emotional connections in your life, being empathetic
is one of the most important characteristics to have. You want to show
others that you have a soft and caring side of you that can empathize with
their struggles. In this example, you can see how someone opens up to you
about something deep to them and you respond with empathy that makes
them feel heard.
You: Hi there, Jean. Are you okay?
Jean: Not really. I’m having the worst day possible.
You: I’m so sorry to hear about that. What’s been going on if you don’t
mind me asking?
Jean: Actually, I’d really love to get another person’s perspective on this
situation. Can I vent quickly?
You: Of course! I’m here to listen.
Jean: My boss completely flipped out on me today and told me that she was
going to fire me if I didn’t make it up to her. Honestly, the way she reacted
was as if I leaked top secret company info. All I did was forget to get her
signature on a document before sending it through. I know it was an
important document, but there was no need to give me a written warning.
She humiliated me in front of the whole office by screaming at the top of her
lungs.
You: That is so awful. I’m honestly so sorry you went through that, you
didn’t deserve it.
Jean: So what do you think? Do you think I was in the wrong?
You: Well, of course it was a mistake, but who doesn’t make minor mistakes
every now and then? You’re not a robot. I’d understand if she were a little
upset, but she was completely out of line to shout at you like that and give
you a written warning. It really wasn’t the worst thing that you did.
Jean: Thank you! That’s exactly how I feel, but none of my colleagues
agreed. They’re too frightened to ever disagree with her.
You (chuckles): Then that just proves who the problem is!
This conversation is the perfect example of how you should comfort
someone going through a hard time. Your friend was frustrated with a work
matter, and you gave her the space and time to vent properly. This made her
feel closer to you, as she was able to be completely open about what she
was feeling. She even asked for your opinion, which shows her interest and
care in what you have to say. By validating her, it strengthened your bond,
as she finally felt heard and seen. You then ended the conversation with a
light-hearted joke, which shows your fun personality.
Example 2 - Being Yourself
You’re trying to make friends with someone new, as you think that you will
click well. You’re trying to find common ground with them, as you talk to
them casually. As you talk to them, you realize they aren’t actually the type
of person you thought they were. You continue the conversation being true
to yourself, regardless of what they may think of you.
You: I must say, I noticed you and thought I had to come up to you. You
look like you have such great energy, which I love!
Stranger: Thanks, man, that’s really sweet of you.
You: So, what are you up to today?
Stranger (offering a cigarette): Nothing much – hey, I’m just on a quick
smoke break before getting back to work. Do you smoke?
You: No, I don’t.
Stranger: Really? I’m not going to lie, that's really lame. Just one cigarette
won’t hurt you; try it.
You: No, thanks. I don’t believe in smoking.
Stranger: Well, I smoke 24/7, so I expect all my friends to as well.
You: Then I hope you enjoy the rest of your day! Bye.
In this example, you can see how to stay true to yourself in a conversation,
even if it makes you seem uncool or awkward. You wanted to make friends
with this individual, but they made it clear that you can only be friends if
you smoke as well. This is not true to your nature or something you agree
with, so instead of causing an argument or doing something that goes
against your beliefs, you calmly leave the conversation.
Example 3 - Using Social Proof
As humans, we look at each other for social proof. As much as you think
that all of your thoughts and decisions are independent, social proof has
played a role in some of your decisions and outcomes in life. You can use
social proof within conversations to build trust and create connections. In
this example, you can see how social proof is used to get your boyfriend to
realize that your relationship will be a lot stronger with this emotional
connection being formed.
You: Hey, love, there’s something I’ve really been wanting to talk to you
about.
Boyfriend: Really? What do you want to talk about?
You: I want to talk about us. I really love where our relationship is going
because I have so much fun with you, and I thoroughly enjoy your company
–
Boyfriend: But?
You: But, I feel like all we focus on in this relationship are the material
things. We’re only concerned about what we do together and how many
gifts we buy for each other, but I want to dig deeper.
Boyfriend: What do you mean?
You: I want to know more about you and what your mind thinks. We’ve
never spoken about our emotions together, or had uncomfortable
conversations that help us learn more about each other.
Boyfriend: That’s true, but why do we need to talk about our emotions if
we’re happy and having so much fun?
You: Well, talking about our emotions is not necessarily a bad thing. It just
means we tell each other how we feel about certain things that we’re going
through, whether it has to do with us or not. I feel like we will feel so much
closer doing this. Couples who talk about their emotions and find comfort
in each other are more likely to have a long, healthy relationship together.
Boyfriend: Really? I didn’t know that. I guess all of my relationships in the
past have been very surface level, so I’ve never really understood the need
for an emotional connection.
You: We have emotional connections with our family members and our best
friends, and I’m sure you can’t picture a life without them. It makes you
closer to people when you’re emotionally connected to them. We already
have so much fun together, so if we embrace a new emotional connection
together, imagine how amazing this relationship could be!
Boyfriend: You’ve convinced me. From now on I will open up about how
I’m feeling more, whether it’s good or bad.
In this example, you can see how to blatantly ask for an emotional
connection from someone by using the principle of social proof. You may
be fearful of asking someone to build an emotional connection with you
because you don’t want to look desperate, but coming out and saying what
you want may be the perfect way to get it. In this conversation, you told
your boyfriend how much emotional connections improve relationships,
and this convinced him that it would be a good thing for your relationship.
Sometimes in life, instead of beating around the bush, we need to ask for
what we want and let others know how it can be beneficial for them.
CHAPTER 6
Listening to Others
"The art of conversation lies in listening." – Malcolm Forbes
In order to successfully engage in small talk, you need to be able to be a
good listener. Unfortunately, not everything is about you and listening to the
sound of your own voice, as it takes two people to have a conversation. If
you want your small talk to be successful, you need to be able to listen to
what other people have to say in response to you.
When you become so focused on what you say during your small talk, you
may find yourself obsessing over your side of the conversation. This means
that you talk for the sake of talking, instead of listening first and responding
appropriately to what the other person has to say. You will get the best
results from small talk when you genuinely hear what the other person has
to say, as you’re more likely to engage in a deeper, more successful
conversation.
The Importance of Listening to Others
When you get wrapped up in small talk, you may find yourself focusing
solely on what you’re saying. We often get so caught up in our own words
that we fail to listen to the people we’re in conversation with. It’s so
important to take a breath and actually listen to what the other person has to
say to you. To have successful small talk, you need to be able to listen
openly and attentively to others.
Improving Communication Skills
You may be experiencing ineffective and poor communication, which
makes you wonder to yourself what’s going wrong. You feel as though
you’re trying your best to communicate with others, but you don’t know
why all of your conversations end up falling short. Sometimes the problem
isn’t about the other person, or your conversation starting skills, but about
how well you listen. Here are a few ways listening to others improves your
communication skills:
Your responses improve. Often we can get into the bad habit of
merely listening to respond. You’re only listening to what the other
person is saying because you want to know when it’s your turn to
respond. However, when you truly listen to what another person has to
say, your responses become better. Your responses become less about
what you want to say, and more about your reaction to what they’ve
said.
You make them feel more heard. With better responses that show
you’re truly listening, you end up making the other person feel more
heard. Trust me, people can tell whether you’re listening to them or not
by the way you respond to them. When your responses are suitable for
the situation and they reflect that you’ve been listening the whole time,
the other person enjoys the conversation more. When individuals
notice that you’re attentively listening to them, they’re more likely to
reciprocate this energy.
You learn more about the other person. Actively listening to others
doesn’t only make them feel better about themselves, but it also helps
you to learn more about others. The whole point of small talk is to
learn more about the people around you, and this wouldn’t be possible
if you don’t actually hear what they’re saying to you. Listening
attentively teaches you so much more about others, so try to take in
every word they say.
You may think that the foundation of good communication is what you say,
but it’s actually how you listen to others. A conversation is a two-way
experience, even if you’re just engaging in small talk. You need to be able
to attentively listen to what people have to say, no matter what the
conversation topic is, as this will lead to successful and effective
communication!
Mastering Your Listening Skills
You may think that you are the perfect listener, but in reality, you’re more
focused on yourself than on what the other person has to say in return. It’s
important to realize when you’re not the perfect listener, because this could
be your downfall that’s taking a toll on your effective communication.
If you discover that your listening skills may not be the best, there’s ways to
improve them. It’s all about being mindful of your words and how you
speak, as this will truly portray whether you’re listening or not. Making that
extra effort to be more attentive and open-minded when you’re listening to
others will not only improve your small talk, but your general
communication as well. You’ll also find that the better you listen to others,
they will listen as attentively in return.
How to Listen More Attentively
Are you someone who really wants to be a better listener, but you can’t help
getting distracted when someone speaks to you for long? You try your best
to listen to what they have to say, but your mind wanders to other topics. It
doesn’t mean you’re a bad person if this is how your mind works, as there
are many people who experience this. However, if you want to answer
appropriately, you need to be able to focus on what the other person has to
say. These are some ways you can be a more attentive listener:
Get out of your head. Do you have a chaotic mind that always feels
busy and filled with thoughts? If you find yourself constantly getting
consumed by your chaotic thoughts, it’s important to find ways to get
out of your head. When you are too occupied by your thoughts, you
will struggle to attentively listen to what other people have to say.
Sometimes you need to get out of your head and just focus on what
other people have to say.
Limit your distractions. Another way to ensure that you listen more
attentively is by limiting your distractions. When you are surrounded
by a distracting environment, or you’re experiencing distracting
thoughts, it can make your mind wander. It’s important to limit your
distractions. If you can’t achieve that, you can try to find ways to avoid
the distraction from consuming your attention. For example, if you
witness people getting into a fight near you, but you’re in a
conversation, avoid looking at the individuals fighting, as this will just
consume all of your attention.
Visualize what’s being spoken about. A great trick to keep your
mind focused on what you’re being told in the moment is visualizing
what you hear. You may be someone who’s better at learning things
through visual aids. When you hear someone speak, your focus
vanishes, and you struggle to keep up with what the speaker is saying.
It’s valuable to visualize everything that they’re saying as they say it,
so you can feel more captivated and interested as they speak.
Showing You’re an Active Listener
You may be doing a great job listening to the other person speak – you’re
soaking up everything they’re saying, and you’re truly being mindful of
their words – but externally you look bored out of your mind and totally
disinterested in the conversation. You want to appear as though you’re
listening so that the person you’re talking to can feel like you’re involved in
the conversation. These are some ways you can appear a more active
listener to others:
Maintain eye contact. Where do your eyes wander when you’re
having a conversation with someone? If you find yourself constantly
dozing and looking around when people are talking to you, it’s going
to look as though you aren’t listening to what they have to say, as well
as thinking of your own things. By maintaining eye contact with the
person you’re talking to, you appear as though all of your attention is
focused on them.
Avoid interrupting. If you want to show the person you’re talking to
that you’re present in the conversation and that you’re actively
listening to them, you need to avoid interrupting them at all costs.
Sometimes when we have lots of thoughts pop into our head as other
people talk, it makes us want to add our own opinion quickly to the
conversation. However, when you interrupt someone as they speak, it
makes it seem as though you aren’t genuinely listening to what they
have to say. Instead of interrupting, you must wait for a pause in the
conversation to add your thoughts.
Ask questions or relate to them. You can also show that you’re being
an active listener by the way you respond to what they have to say.
When you respond in a way that’s relative to what the other person has
said, it shows that you’ve been listening attentively. This is why it’s
valuable for you to ask questions that are relative to what they’re
talking about, to show you’re interested. You can also personally relate
to what they’re talking to, but when you do this, you must ensure you
don’t make the conversation all about yourself.
If you want to make the best impression with the person you’re speaking to,
you should show them that you are engaged in what they have to say. When
you show that you’re an active listener, the other person is going to feel
more excited and engaged in the conversation.
Listening With an Open Mind
Not only is it important to be more attentive when you’re communicating
with others, but it’s also important to listen to what people have to say with
an open mind. We can get so stuck in our usual habits, routines, and
opinions that it gives us the perception that everything must be how we
think it should be. However, this can give us a closed mind when we listen
to other peoples’ problems and circumstances.
When you have a very narrowed view on how life should be and how
people should behave, you don’t make a good listener. You may be listening
to every word the other person is saying to you, but you don’t respond or
think in a way that a good listener would. You end up judging the person for
what they told you, and you may even provide them with criticism that they
didn’t ask for.
You need to be able to listen with an open mind so that you can understand
what the other person is saying to you. Don’t jump straight into making
assumptions and judging their situation, but instead listen attentively with
care so that you can have a better understanding of their situation.
For example, if someone you’re making friends with tells you something
serious and close to their heart, you need to listen to what they’re saying
with care. Although what they did may go against your beliefs and
opinions, you may be surprised to change your perspective after hearing
their full story.
CHAPTER 7
The Power of Nonverbal
Communication
"Body language is a very powerful tool. We had body language before we
had speech, and apparently, 80% of what you understand in a conversation
is read through the body, not the words." – Deborah Bull
Communication is not only about verbal conversation through small talk, but
it’s also about nonverbal communication; they work hand in hand. It helps us
gather exactly what someone is trying to say, not through their words, but
how they deliver them physically. We gather a lot through people’s body
language without even realizing it. When you practice small talk, you must
find ways to incorporate nonverbal communication to help make your
message clearer.
Our body language, mannerisms, and facial expressions all add to what
we’re saying and thinking. This is why it is so important to be mindful of
your nonverbal communication, as it helps to add on to your verbal
statements, as well as helps you to say things you struggle to put into words.
Our nonverbal expressions show when we’re happy, upset, or uncomfortable
in a situation.
The Value of Nonverbal Communication
You may be thinking to yourself, How on earth does your body language
impact a conversation, especially when you’re merely engaging in small
talk? However, how you use your body language, mannerisms, and facial
expressions tells other people a lot more than you realize. These are the five
roles nonverbal communication can play in your conversation:
Repetition. Our nonverbal communication can repeat and emphasize
the words we verbally say. When your body language and facial
expressions reflect the words you’re saying and the tone you’re
speaking in, it essentially repeats the message you’re trying to get
across. This emphasizes to the other person what you’re trying to say to
them, and they can tell you mean what you’re saying verbally.
Contradiction. On the other hand, your nonverbal communication
could contradict what you're saying verbally. Your mouth may be
saying one thing, but your mannerisms and body language are saying
another thing. This can be confusing for the people you talk to, as they
don’t know whether you really mean what you say or not. For example,
you may be saying you’re upset with someone, but you’re smiling with
a happy facial expression. This makes it seem as though you aren’t
genuinely upset.
Substitution. When you’re experiencing a situation that is hard to talk
about, all you can use is nonverbal communication. We often find
ourselves overwhelmed by emotions and thoughts that we don’t know
the right words to use to express ourselves. This makes it valuable to
substitute verbal communication for more nonverbal tactics. You can
say a lot with your body language, as well as show others how you feel.
If people can see that your body language is closed off in a situation, it
may show them that you’re feeling uncomfortable.
Complementing. Using nonverbal communication can even
complement what we’re trying to communicate. As with repetition,
using body language to emphasize your message can make it a lot more
impactful. For example, you may be consoling a friend, and after you
say kind words, you give them a hug. This action complements the
words you’ve used, and they help your friend to feel even more special
and heard.
Accent. Sometimes words aren’t enough, and you have to use
nonverbal communication to accent what you’ve said. Nonverbal
techniques can often act as statements that bring attention to your words
and force people to listen. For example, if a parent is really frustrated
with their child’s behavior, they may reprimand them and stomp their
foot afterward, to show how truly frustrated they are. Actions can speak
louder than words sometimes, and when people see physical
movements and gestures as you speak, it adds on to what you’re trying
to communicate verbally.
After reading how nonverbal communication adds value to your words, you
may discover that you use it on a daily basis in your life. Whether you’re
aware of it or not, you use your body language to communicate with others.
Not only do we use our nonverbal communication when talking to others,
but other people use it around us. Believe it or not, but you interpret people’s
body language toward you all day, and this often happens subconsciously
without you even noticing it.
Types of Nonverbal Communication
There are various types of nonverbal communication that can mean different
things. We all use nonverbal communication on a daily basis without even
realizing it. You may consider nonverbal communication as how you use
your hands as you speak or the facial expressions you use, but nonverbal
communication can be exemplified in many different ways.
We don’t realize all the various ways we use nonverbal communication
within every conversation we engage in. Here are some different types of
nonverbal communication that you’ve used at some point in conversation.
Facial expressions: This is one of the more obvious ways of using
nonverbal communications, as we all use facial expressions to reflect
how we feel. Some of us may have more pronounced facial expressions
than others, but no matter how subtle or obvious your facial expressions
are, they are a clear way to communicate with people. If you want to
show someone you’re angry with them, your facial expressions display
this rage. When people are quiet because they’re going through
emotions, you can tell by their facial expressions what they’re feeling.
Hand gestures: Our hands communicate with others so much more
than we give them credit for. Using hand gestures is a clear way to
accent your communication or even retrieve someone’s attention
altogether. If you want to welcome someone and beckon them toward
you, you can use hand gestures to show them you want to talk to them.
If you want to bring peoples’ attention to something, you can point or
wave your hands. You can also use hand gestures in a more subtle way,
by using them during conversation to add on to your words.
Posture and body placement: Consider your posture and body
placement as you speak to someone. Something that seems so small and
insignificant can have some real meaning behind it. When you have a
slumped posture, your arms are covering yourself, and your feet and
entire body are pointed away from the person you’re talking to, it
signifies that you don’t want to be in conversation with the person
you’re talking to. It may be a sign that you’re uncomfortable or
disinterested. When your posture is good, you’re standing upright, and
your body placement is open and welcoming, it indicates that you’re
confident and happy to be talking to the other person.
Touching and space: Another form of nonverbal connection is how
you touch people and use space. There are ways you can communicate
through physical touch which don’t have to be seen as intimate and
romantic. When you give your child a pat on the back for doing a good
job, it shows that you are communicating your pride. The way you
utilize space with your body also says a lot about what you’re thinking.
For example, if you stand far away from someone, with your back
facing them, it can show that you don’t want to be near that individual.
Tone: Nonverbal communication is not only expressed through
physical movements and actions, but also through the tone of voice you
use. How you say things makes a big impact on the message you’re
trying to get across. As people, we listen to the tone people use when
they talk to us as it can portray exactly how the other person is feeling.
If you use a stern and assertive tone, the listener will know that you’re
being serious in the situation. However, if your tone is happy and calm,
they know that you’re engaging in a friendly conversation.
All of these nonverbal forms of communication occur naturally when we
speak to people. We use every single one of these nonverbal communication
tactics, and it enhances and influences the messages or ideas we verbally
communicate with people. Being aware of how you use your nonverbal body
language can help you to utilize it in a more effective way.
How to Utilize Nonverbal Communication
If you want to take your communication to the next level when you’re
engaging in small talk, you should consider utilizing nonverbal
communication. You may find yourself saying one thing verbally, but your
nonverbal communication portrays something different. You want to be able
to use your body language to emphasize and add on to the message that you
want to get across.
Positive Body Language
If you want to work toward utilizing body language to improve your
communication, you should know how to make the most of positive body
language. There is a way for you to positively portray yourself by merely
using the right type of body language. You may be wondering how on earth
you can portray positive energy with the use of your body, but the answer is
actually quite simple.
By opening up your body, using space wisely, and giving the right facial
expressions, you can exude a more positive energy. Positive body language
may be something you’ve never actively noticed before, but that doesn’t
mean it hasn't had an influence on your behavior before.
The SOFTEN Technique
One way you can work on displaying more positive body language is by
utilizing the SOFTEN technique. This technique can remind you to be more
positive and friendly to others as you speak to them. It can be so easy to
forget about your mannerisms and facial expressions, which may make you
appear in a way you never intended. When you find yourself forgetting how
to express yourself nonverbally, you should consider the SOFTEN
technique, which stands for the following:
Smile: A simple smile can go a long way when you’re trying to make a
good impression. When you smile at someone as you talk to them, it
makes you appear friendlier and softer.
Open posture: You should then consider what your posture is like at
that moment. Are you slouched and closed off? If you notice that you
are, you should work on opening your posture so that you can appear
more welcoming.
Forward lean: If you’re trying to get closer to the person you’re
speaking to, don’t be afraid to get close to them. By appropriately
leaning forward, it shows you’re more engaged in the conversation.
When using this body language, ensure the other person is comfortable
and happy; you don’t want to invade someone else’s personal space.
Touch: Using touch effectively within your conversation to emphasize
your point can be quite effective, e.g., giving them a tap on the
shoulder, hugging them, or giving them a pat on the back. As with
leaning forward, you need to be able to know when it’s appropriate to
touch the person you’re talking to. If they are uncomfortable with being
touched, avoid doing it.
Eye contact: Eye contact is a valuable way to show someone you’re
present in the moment. When we give eye contact to the people we’re
speaking to, it shows that we’re focused on them and the conversation
at hand. Different forms of eye contact can also communicate different
things to people. For example, you may give a flirty glance to your
crush that you want to have a date with.
Nod: You’re in a conversation with someone, you’re listening to every
word they’re saying, and you want to find a way to show them that
you’re attentively listening to them. A great way to show that you’re
engaged and focused on what someone has to say is by nodding your
head as they speak. Using nods can also signify other forms of
communication that are often positive, such as greeting and agreeing.
If you ever find yourself in a tricky spot with your communication, just think
about the SOFTEN technique. We aren’t always aware of our body language
and how it’s being perceived by others. Being aware of how you’re using
nonverbal communication can help you discover when it’s necessary to use
this SOFTEN technique to appear more friendly and positive in any
situation!
Examples of Suitable Nonverbal Communication
Understanding how to utilize nonverbal communication is crucial, as it can
help you to have that extra edge and success when you’re talking to others.
When you find yourself in the moment speaking to others, you may find it
challenging to be aware of how you’re communicating to others physically;
however, it’s important to work toward being more aware of your nonverbal
communication.
There are different scenarios and situations we experience in life that require
us to utilize nonverbal communication. Sometimes our words aren’t enough,
and adding body language to our communication enhances the message to
others. Even small talk requires nonverbal communication, as it can improve
any conversation you’re engaging in. These are some examples where body
language enhances and improves a conversation.
Example 1 - Using Hand Gestures
When you’re using small talk to speak about something you’re passionate
about, you may want to emphasize how truly interested you are in this
conversation topic. A great way to show interest and passion in something
you’re talking about is by using hand gestures. Expressing yourself through
suitable hand gestures can actually accent what you’re verbally
communicating. This example will show you how hand gestures can be used
to portray or emphasize a message.
Friend: Did you hear about the screenwriting competition being held?
You (lifting hands in excitement): Yes! I heard about it, and I really want to
submit my latest screenplay, but I don’t think I’m good enough to win.
Friend: Don’t say that. I’m sure your script is a great competitor. Tell me
about it.
You: Really, do you want to hear about it?
You proceed to explain your script in detail, and when you do this, you use
vibrant and expressive hand gestures. As you describe the exciting parts of
your screenplay, your passion is visible through your hand gestures. This
draws your friend’s attention, as they can see how passionate you are and
how exciting it is for you. They end up loving your idea and they encourage
you to apply to the competition.
Example 2 - Positive Body Language
When you’re trying to make a good impression on someone, there is no
better time to use positive body language. When you’re talking to someone
you don’t know, they’re less aware of your communication habits, so you
need to add suitable positive body language to present yourself to the best of
your ability. In this example, you can see how positive body language is
used to appear friendlier.
You (reaching out for a handshake): Hi there, how are you doing? I’m
Rebecca.
New colleague (shakes hand): Hi! I’m Sarah, the new employee.
You: It’s so great to finally have a new addition to the team; we’ve been
struggling with a massive workload! But, how has your first day been so
far?
Sarah: It’s been a little scary. Everyone is very intimidating and serious
here. You’re the first person to actually talk to me casually.
You: I know, everyone is wound pretty tight around here. Don’t tell them I
said that. (smiles and giggles)
Sarah (laughs): Trust me, I won’t.
You (gesturing toward yourself): Well, just know you have a work friend
here. You can come to me anytime! Welcome to the office. (leans in for a
hug)
Sarah (engages in hug): Thank you so much, Rebecca. Enjoy the rest of
your day!
Through this conversation you can see how you’ve made a great first
impression, as well as how you made your new colleague feel comfortable.
This wasn’t just achieved by the words you used, as you used positive
nonverbal communication that made the other person feel welcomed and
included.
By starting with a handshake, you showed your interest to communicate with
Sarah. Using friendly and positive facial expressions made me realize that
you were more relaxed and friendly than your other colleagues. Ending off
the conversation with a hug helped her leave the conversation with a positive
first impression of you. She may even rely on you as a great work friend to
help her find her way in the new job.
How to Read Body Language
Now that you know how to use body language effectively in your
communication, you should consider how to read other peoples’ body
language. You’re not the only one who can use their body language to
communicate, as every single one of us utilizes it subconsciously on a daily
basis. Being able to read body language is valuable, as it can help you gain a
better understanding of what other people are trying to say to you. These are
just a few tips that can help you read body language better and improve your
communication:
Pay attention to body language. When you want to become better at
reading body language, you should try your best to pay attention to the
body language of people around you. We often ignore nonverbal
dialogue, as it slips to the back of our mind, but being mindful and
aware of peoples’ body language toward you can teach you a lot.
Understand body language. Different uses of body language mean
different things. This makes it important for you to have an
understanding of what different types of body language mean. You
probably have a better grasp of different forms of body language after
reading what’s above, but it’s helpful to learn more about nonverbal
communication.
Trust your instincts. As much as understanding the set meanings of
specific body language is valuable, it’s also important to trust your own
instincts. Although you may see the person you’re talking to smiling
and laughing with you, if you notice that their smile is off and they’re
hiding their true feelings, you may be right. Sometimes people use their
body language to hide what they’re truly feeling inside. You should
trust your instincts when reading body language, as you may pick up
how someone really feels, especially if you know this individual and
their mannerisms well.
Identify nonverbal cues. Sometimes reading body language is
important because you can notice nonverbal cues that the speaker is
trying to bring to your attention. Sometimes people find it hard to
communicate specific things, so they use these nonverbal cues as a
substitute. You should be aware of different body language that stands
out to you because they may be quite subtle. For example, if someone is
facing their body away from you and they’re trying to walk away as
you talk to them, this may be a sign that they want to leave but they
don’t know how to verbally say it.
Once you’re able to identify the speaker’s body language as they talk, you
should determine how to respond to it. Do you know how to respond to
different types of nonverbal communication in the most suitable way? You
may find yourself ignoring body language, as you don’t think it’s significant,
but how you respond can influence the rest of your communication with this
individual.
You need to be able to distinguish between good and bad body language so
that you can respond suitably. If you notice that someone has positive body
language toward you, then keep up what you’re doing because you’re doing
something right. You may also want to reciprocate the positive body
language, to show that you’re just engaged in the conversation as they are.
However, if you can tell they are portraying negative or uncomfortable body
language, it’s important to work on your communication to make them more
comfortable. Maybe you’re invading their personal space, so you need to
give them more space to feel more comfortable. On the other hand, they may
feel worried that the conversation isn’t going well, and you can use positive
nonverbal communication to show them that you’re enjoying yourself with
them. You can nod, smile, laugh, or give them a pat on the back in a friendly
manner.
When you notice someone isn’t enjoying small talk with you, sometimes the
best way to deal with it is by using positive body language toward them.
Their perception of the conversation may change, as they become more
excited to talk to you.
CHAPTER 8
Avoiding Conversation Barriers,
Blunders, and Awkwardness
"A challenge only becomes an obstacle when you bow to it." – Ray Davis
You may HATE small talk because you have a negative association to it.
When you think of small talk, you are reminded of how awkward you are,
as well as the conversation barriers and blunders you experience. If you
actually want to enjoy and reap the benefits of small talk, you need to be
able to avoid these barriers and awkwardness during small talk.
The best way to achieve this is by practicing small talk confidently, and
avoiding the major don'ts when it comes to small talk. There are specific
communication problems you can avoid that will help your small talk to be
less awkward and restrictive. If you find yourself faced with social anxiety,
it can present you with obstacles during small talk; however, social anxiety
is something you can work on. Through this chapter, you’ll be provided
with tips and steps to help you overcome your social anxiety.
Small Talk Blunders
You find yourself getting into a good rhythm as you engage in small talk.
The other person is engaging and enjoying themselves, and you can notice a
connection forming. You keep going with the conversation, but all of a
sudden the whole vibe of the conversation shifts. The one thing you’ve said
completely changed the energy of the conversation and things become
awkward once again. You have no idea what went wrong and what changed
the energy of your small talk experience.
We all experience blunders in conversations, as we can often find ourselves
saying the wrong things at the wrong time. Having a small talk blunder isn’t
the end of the world, as you can recover from it. If you want to learn how to
move on from these small talk mistakes, you need to be able to identify
what mistake you may have made in the conversation. These are some
common small talk blunders that can ruin the momentum of your
conversation.
Giving the Wrong Compliment
When you give someone a compliment, you may assume that anything is
good to say because at the end of the day, a compliment is a good thing.
Unfortunately, there are some compliments that can be taken the wrong
way. You may find yourself giving a compliment innocently, but to the
other person it comes off as a backhanded compliment that they don’t
appreciate. These are some reasons why you may be giving the wrong
compliment that dampens your small talk:
Backhanded compliments: Some insults can be disguised as
compliments, but everyone knows they’re just backhanded
compliments. If you’re guilty of giving someone a backhanded
compliment, you may not be aware of it, but this doesn’t stop the other
person from getting offended. An example of a backhanded
compliment would include, “You throw well for a girl.” Although it
may sound like you’re saying they throw well, you’re essentially
insulting their ability to throw because of their gender. Providing a
backhanded compliment is enough to silence a conversation.
Ulterior motives: Compliments are received well when they appear
genuine and true. When you compliment someone with an ulterior
motive, people can notice it. If you’re trying to compliment someone
just so that you can get something from them, they will end up leaving
the conversation offended. This will ultimately ruin your small talk, as
it appears insincere.
When you want to compliment people during small talk, it’s important to
consider what you’re trying to say and how you word your compliment.
You need to ensure that your compliment is appropriate and makes the other
person feel good about themselves. It can be easy to say something they
take the wrong way because of the ways it’s worded.
How to Master Remembering Names
You’re having a lovely conversation with a new friend and you’re really
beginning to click. The conversation is flowing, you’re laughing, and you
can sense that the bond is growing between you. All of a sudden the whole
vibe gets ruined because you call them by the wrong name. No one likes to
feel like their name isn’t worth remembering, so it’s bound to cause a speed
bump in your smoothly flowing conversation.
If you want to stay in the good books with the people you talk to, as well as
connect with them on a deeper level, you need to be able to remember their
names. When you’re talking to someone or referring to them, it’s more
effective to use their names, as this makes it feel more personalized for
them. Being able to remember the names of the people you’re talking to is
so crucial, so here are a few tips that can help you become a master at
remembering names:
Repeat their name. As soon as you meet someone new, that’s the time
to work on learning their name. You want to know it from that day
forward so that you can call them out when you see them in the future.
When someone introduces themselves to you for the first time, you
should repeat their name back to them. For example, if you meet
someone at the gym and they say, “Hi, I’m Byron,” you can say, “Nice
to meet you, Byron,” and then proceed to introduce yourself. Saying
the name back to them helps you to remember their name
subconsciously.
Associate their name with something. Another easy trick to use
when trying to learn names is making an association game. To do this
you need to observe the person you’re speaking to. Maybe something
they say to you can be something you remember them by. For
example, the person you’re talking to may be talking a lot about their
accounting job, so you can remember them as Tom from accounting.
You can choose anything spontaneous or suitable that will help you to
remember names. Maybe you use a word that rhymes with their name.
Connect face with name. You may be the type of person who’s great
with faces but terrible with names. You can remember someone’s face
instantly, but when it comes to their name, it’s a distant memory. If this
is the case for you, you should try this trick to connect someone’s face
to their name. Start by looking at the person you’re talking to and
notice if they have any distinguished features. Maybe they have bright
hair, or a big nose. Think of something distinctive that you can use to
remember their name.
Once you’ve learnt someone’s name, you’ll find it easier to remember with
these tips. Whenever you talk to someone, it’s valuable to refer to them
using their name, as this makes them feel more special as you talk to them.
Overcoming Social Anxiety
Another reason why you may be struggling with your small talk is because
you experience social anxiety. Although reading all of these tips and tricks
throughout this book are helpful, as soon as you actually have to practice
them on someone, you find yourself getting nervous. Many people suffer
from social anxiety, but just because you may have it, doesn’t mean you’re
stuck with it.
Steps to Overcome Your Social Anxiety
If you feel as though your social anxiety is setting you back in your small
talk conversations, you should find ways to overcome this anxiety. Social
anxiety can set back your communication skills, which gives you a false
illusion that you suck at communicating with others. When you leave your
social anxiety behind, you’ll be surprised to discover how great you can
actually become at communicating and engaging in small talk.
You’re having a conversation with someone, and you want to build a
connection with them. You’re trying to remember all the tips and tricks for
successful small talk that you learnt through this book, but your mind goes
completely blank. You find yourself too stressed and worried to get through
the conversation. If you ever find yourself in this predicament, you must
follow these steps:
1. Stop and calm down. When you find yourself getting frazzled when
you’re engaging in small talk because of your social anxiety, it’s okay
to take a moment to stop and breathe. Instead of stuttering on your
words and freezing up, take some time to yourself to calm down. Try
to control your breath and calm your mind down. Once you calm
down, it’ll be easier to think with a clearer mind.
2. Own your social anxiety. You may be embarrassed by your social
anxiety, as you fear that it makes you different. It’s important to realize
that there's nothing wrong with telling someone you struggle with
social anxiety. If others can see you’re struggling to talk, it may make
the conversation awkward. When you open up about your troubles
with social anxiety it can clear the air, as well as maybe making you
feel less tense and anxious.
3. Use safe topics. Previously in this book, we discussed some safe
topics that you can use to get a conversation started. If you find
yourself experiencing social anxiety and you have no idea what to say,
this is when you can make use of your safe topics. These safe topics
can be used to start up a conversation again, which can calm you down
by making the conversation less awkward.
4. Just smile. Being anxious can make you extremely tense and stressed.
Although you may think you’re just stressing internally, you may be
displaying it externally. You could look very serious and stressed,
which may make the other person think you aren’t enjoying the
conversation. You need to relax and smile because this doesn’t only
give a good impression, but smiling can convince you to calm down.
These steps may sound very simple, but they are completely effective.
When you have social anxiety, you may tend to overthink all of your
conversations. Sometimes all you need to do is calm down and take the
conversation less seriously. Small talk isn’t a matter of life or death, so you
should approach it with fun and casual energy. This will make the
experience more enjoyable for you.
Tips to Conquer Social Anxiety
If you use the previous steps when you find yourself struggling with social
anxiety and still don’t know how to move on with the conversation in a
calm state, these tips will help you conquer social anxiety once and for all.
One positive thing about social anxiety is that you don’t have to be stuck
with it forever, especially if you do the necessary work to get over your
fears.
Confidence is Key
One reason why you may be struggling to converse with others is because
you lack confidence in yourself. Being shy and nervous is a sign that you
aren’t confident in yourself and what you have to say. You fear that you’ll
embarrass yourself or that no one will care about what you have to say. It’s
important for you to have more confidence in yourself, because at the end
of the day, everyone is just winging it.
When you talk with confidence and assurance in yourself, people are more
likely to listen to you and care about what you have to say. Even if you
aren’t confident in yourself, you should try and fake it, as this will convince
yourself that you know what you’re doing. Being more confident in
yourself and your ability to participate in small talk will help you firmly
overcome your social anxiety.
Prepare Yourself for Social Encounters
If you’re aware that you're going to be having a social encounter and it’s
making you anxious, then why not prepare for it? You can prepare in
advance for social occasions that may bring you stress, because this will
help you calm down and feel more prepared. When you want to prepare
yourself for social encounters, then you should do the following:
1. Consider who you’ll talk to. The first thing you need to do is
consider the social encounter you’re anxious about. Are you feeling
nervous to go to a wedding for a friend, maybe you’re going to a
serious work event, or you could even be going on a date for the first
time in a while? Think about what social occasion is bringing you
anxiety and who you would be expected to talk to. Once you know
who it is or what event you’re attending, you can follow the next steps.
2. Find topics of conversation. If you know the type of people you’ll be
speaking to in this social event, you’ll be able to come up with suitable
topics. For example, if you’re seeing people at a work event, then you
should come up with work-related topics to bring up. Having these
topics will act as a security blanket for you, as you’re able to use them
when you find yourself in a tough spot in a conversation.
3. Consider the worst. Once you prepare some topics you can talk
about, there’s not much else you can plan. You can’t predict how your
conversations will go exactly, but you can prepare yourself to handle
the worst. If you have social anxiety, you’ll find that you constantly
psych yourself up for the worst, but you need to ask yourself, What’s
the worst that can actually happen? When you consider this, you’ll
probably determine that the worst outcome of the conversation is that
it might be awkward, but that won’t kill you. Having this mindset
helps you to be prepared for anything, and you’ll be pleasantly
surprised when the conversation ends up going well!
After following the previous tips, you will find that you feel more prepared
to take on any social situation. Doing this helps you to approach your social
situations with more confidence and assurance, which means that you can
have successful small talk that doesn’t cause you to crumble under pressure.
Overcome Shyness and Fear
Being shy and fearful of speaking is a problem many people deal with, but
you shouldn’t let this fear stop you from socializing and putting yourself out
there. You deserve to build connections, meet new people, and show others
the best version of yourself. Although you may be shy and fearful, you have
so much potential that you can use it to socialize.
Sometimes when we find ourselves nervous to socialize with others, we
need to go to the opposite spectrum and embrace who we are. You have a
unique and special personality that no one can notice because you’re too
busy hiding yourself. It’s time to break out of that shell and be yourself
when communicating with others.
It may be scary to put yourself out there, but if people grow to like you, it
shows you that they want to connect with you because of your bright
personality. The best way to leave fear behind is by completely getting out
of your comfort zone and challenging yourself.
Practice Makes Perfect
Finally, the last tip is that practice makes perfect. You won’t be able to let
go of your social anxiety if you don’t actually practice small talk with
others. You need to be able to have these conversations to overcome your
fear. Although you may not think you’re capable of successfully engaging
in conversations, you’ll be surprised to see what you can accomplish with
the proper practice.
Small talk is a great place to start when you suffer with social anxiety, as it
can help you talk to strangers and form connections. To overcome this fear,
you need to gradually expose yourself to social settings, as well as push
yourself out of your comfort zone. Start small and progressively do things
more and more out of your comfort zone. Over time you’ll become a
professional at talking to people, whether it’s a group of people, a stranger,
or someone you know.
CHAPTER 9
Strategic Small Talk for
Conversation Hurdles
"It was impossible to get a conversation going, everybody was talking too
much." – Yogi Berra
Unfortunately, not all conversations or small talk experiences are going to
be seamless and perfect. No matter how much you try to avoid the barriers
and the awkwardness, some small talk experiences may not be the best.
This is due to how you feel in that moment, as well as who you’re talking
to. Although you may be putting effort into your small talk, the other person
may seem disinterested or uncooperative.
If you do come across small talk that doesn’t go smoothly, don’t despair, as
there are ways you can tackle these conversation hurdles. When you
become a master at small talk and you learn all the strategies you can use,
then you will find it a lot easier to overcome any communication obstacles
that come your way.
Troubleshooting Conversation Hurdles
As much as you may try your hardest to have the most perfect small talk
experience, you may find yourself coming across conversation hurdles. As
we touched briefly on in the previous chapter, there are conversation
disruptions that can provide challenges for your conversation. Sometimes
you need to troubleshoot these conversation hurdles that you experience so
that conversation can run smoothly once again.
There are various different problems that may cause a conversation to grow
stagnant or ineffective. These are just a few issues you may face that disrupt
the flow.
Conversation Partner Gets Frustrated
One of the reasons why conversation may not run smoothly is because your
conversation partner may begin to get frustrated. Being in a conversation
where you feel unheard can be extremely frustrating, as no one wants to
hear someone else talking nonstop. This can cause the conversation to
become one-sided and less enjoyable for the person you’re talking to. Here
are some ways you may have a frustrated conversation partner.
Interrupting The Speaker
Nothing can ruin the vibe of a conversation more than interrupting what
someone has to say. Let’s face it, no one likes to be interrupted as they
speak, as it makes you feel unheard, as well as it ruins the flow of what
you’re trying to talk about. When you’re in an exciting conversation and
you want to respond promptly, you may find yourself interrupting someone
else to get your point across.
Interrupting the speaker once or twice may not disturb them, as they just
continue speaking, but the more you interrupt them, the worse the small talk
will become. You will notice that the person you’re speaking to becomes
really frustrated, which may even result in them not wanting to talk
anymore.
This leaves the conversation awkward and silent because the other person
doesn’t want to engage in a conversation where they’re not being heard
properly. You need to give other people the spotlight and avoid interrupting.
Even if you have questions you want to ask, you should wait for a pause in
the conversation to ask them.
Not Knowing When to Stop Talking
Are you someone with verbal diarrhea? You may be the type of person who
loves talking and never knows when to stop. Although you may think it’s
saving the conversation, you’re most probably frustrating your conversation
partner. It’s important to know when a conversation is coming to an end, as
you don’t want to keep someone longer than they want to be.
When you’re known as the person who talks peoples’ ears off without
letting them escape, you’ll find people avoid having conversations with
you. It’s important to notice when someone wants to leave a conversation
with you. Stopping a conversation doesn’t mean that you’ve failed small
talk, it can actually mean that you understand social cues.
Conversation Stalls
We’ve all been there, when the conversation is going smoothly for a while,
but you find yourself stalling. Now you and the other person are just sitting
there in awkward silence, trying to avoid eye contact. Having a
conversation stall isn’t the end of the world, as you can come back from it.
These are some ways your conversation may stall.
Saying Something Controversial
One way a conversation can stall is if you use controversial topics, or if you
end up offending the person you’re talking to. If you want to engage in
some light-hearted and friendly conversation, you need to avoid
controversial topics at all costs. No matter how interesting a controversial
topic may be, it’s not worth being brought up, as it can create a very
uncomfortable small talk experience that turns into an argument. Some
people have really strong opinions about certain things and can get deeply
offended, so it’s valuable to avoid controversial topics such as politics,
religion, and vaccinations.
When bringing up such topics, you could hit a nerve with the other person.
Although you may not be the type of person to judge someone based on
their beliefs, some people may not be the same. You could merely say that
you support a specific political party, and this can change the other person’s
entire impression of you. It’s better to be safe than sorry when it comes to
controversial topics, as they can be the quickest way to end small talk.
Even if you avoid all the controversial topics, you may say something that
you think is harmless, but it ends up hitting a nerve with the person you’re
talking to. When something like this happens, you may become puzzled
because you have no idea what you've said that’s so wrong. However, if you
do find yourself in this position, you can find ways to recover the
conversation, this will be discussed in the rest of this chapter.
Awkward Silences
Awkward silences can often feel as though they are going on for hours and
it’s the worst way to experience a conversation stall. The longer the
awkward silence is, the harder it can be to recover the conversation. These
are some general causes of awkward silences that could be stalling your
conversations:
You’ve reached the end of a subject or conversation topic.
You experience contrasting opinions.
Both parties are too shy to bring up new topics.
There are many reasons why you may be experiencing awkward silences in
your conversation, and although it may feel as though you can’t recover
from this awkwardness, any conversation can be salvaged. If you are
confident and motivated to move the conversation along, anything is
achievable.
Examples of How to Troubleshoot a Conversation
Instead of providing you with tips and tricks to troubleshoot your
conversations, it’s more valuable and effective for you to see how you can
accomplish this through conversation. How can you recover a stalled
conversation, start a conversation, or make it up to your frustrated
conversation partner. Down below are a few examples that can help you
discover how to salvage your conversation and make it less awkward.
Example 1 - Troubleshooting Conversation Mistakes
Unfortunately, none of us are perfect, so we’re bound to make mistakes
during conversation every now and then. You may say something that you
regret that ends up offending someone, or you could take full control over
the conversation without even realizing it. You’re not a bad communicator
if you mess up conversations every now and then; the key to successful
communication is being able to identify when you’re in the wrong. In this
example, you can see how you can troubleshoot a conversation when you
end up taking it over.
Partner: There’s something I really wanted to talk to you about. Today at
work my boss said the funniest thing, and that reminded me of you.
You: Really? Actually, that reminds me that I also want to tell you
something about work.
Partner: Okay, cool, you can tell me after my story. So, my boss was talking
about our sales, and he said that he’s running an office competition for who
gets the most sales. Whoever wins the competition gets a prize of their
choice, within a certain budget, of course. Now, remember when we’re
talking about getting a new fridge?
You: Yes, I remember that. The worst thing happened the other day when I
got home. I noticed the freezer was leaking, and there was water all over
the floor! I almost slipped and seriously hurt myself.
Partner: Sorry about that babe, but back to what I was saying. My sales
have been doing really well –
You: That’s great, babe! Actually, that reminds me of my story…I’m so
sorry, babe. I can see you’re getting frustrated because I keep on
interrupting you. Please finish your story, I want to hear!
Partner: Well, today the boss announced the winner and it’s me. We’re
getting a new fridge!
You: Wow! I’m so proud of you, babe! I’m going to make a nice meal for
you just to celebrate.
This conversation is a great example of how you can salvage a conversation
when you steal the limelight. Your partner wanted to discuss their day and
you ended up interrupting them at every opportunity. However, when you
noticed what you were doing, you made sure to make your partner feel
special again.
Example 2 - Troubleshooting Conversation Stalls
Experiencing awkward silences during conversations is never pleasant, as it
can make it challenging to bond and connect with the person you’re talking
to. Having awkward silence in a conversation can feel like a massive stall,
but they are easier to recover from than you may realize. This conversation
shows you how you can casually recover a conversation from awkward
silence:
Friend: My boyfriend and I went on a trip, and it was absolutely amazing.
We went to a game reserve, and it was such a beautiful experience. Have
you done any traveling recently?
You: Ugh, I wish! I really want to go on holiday, but unfortunately the funds
are tight at the moment. But I’m so glad you’ve been traveling, it sounds
like so much fun.
Friend: It’s been the best experience traveling and going for adventures
with my boyfriend.
You: I can only imagine!
(Awkward silence)
You: Sorry, don’t mind me. I was just thinking about something. I realized
that I forgot to send something in for work and I know that my boss will
scrutinize me for that. Do you have a good work relationship with your
boss?
Friend: My boss despises me, so we definitely don’t have a good working
relationship. She finds a fault in every little thing I do, and it’s honestly just
a draining experience coming to work because of her.
You: That’s awful! Bosses need to realize that they do more harm than good
when they shout at us and treat us badly. It’s not good for office morale.
This example shows you how you can casually get your conversation
flowing after you experience a stall. When awkward silence occurs it may
feel like the conversation is at its end, but if you start a new topic with
confidence, it will be as though there was no conversation stall to begin
with.
Different People, Different Approach
One thing that’s important to consider when you’re trying to improve your
conversation skills is that different people require different approaches in
conversation. If you want to have successful small talk and you want to
relate to the person you’re talking to, you may need to get on their level to
achieve this. Understanding how to do this will help you to practice small
talk in the most effective manner.
Interacting With a Group
If you find yourself engaging in conversation with a group of people, you
may find that you’re more intimidated and fearful to communicate,
especially if you struggle with social anxiety. When you find yourself in a
group conversation, it can be scary to speak up and join a conversation. You
fear that you say something, and your words get drowned out by everyone
else. These are some tips that can help you to approach group conversations
better:
Greet everyone. If you are approaching a group conversation and you
want to get involved, it’s important to start off by greeting everyone in
the group. You want to make your presence known so that people want
to include you in the group conversation. If there are people in this
group that you don’t know, you should introduce yourself to them.
Speak up. The key to being heard in a group of people is to speak up
when you have something to say. When you mumble and talk under
your breath, no one will hear you and they’ll end up talking right over
you. In group settings, you need to be able to have confidence in
yourself so that you can speak up. Saying what you’re thinking, loudly,
proudly, and with conviction. This will help you to be heard in any
conversation.
Listen to others. Interacting in a group setting is not just about being
heard by others, as you also need to make an effort to listen to others.
You can talk and talk all you want, but you don’t want to be known as
the conversation hog who doesn’t let others talk. It’s also important to
listen attentively so that you can have a suitable response to other
people. This allows you to understand what they’re saying, so that you
can build on what is being spoken about.
You may be intimidated when you know you have to talk with a group of
people. Although it can be scary, you shouldn’t let that overwhelm you, as
there are some benefits to group conversations. It can open you up to
speaking to more people and building more connections. Once you’re able
to tackle a group conversation, one-on-one small talk interactions will seem
less intimidating to you.
Interacting One-On-One
When you’re interacting one-on-one with someone, you may find that it’s a
lot less intimidating for you. Having one-on-one conversation allows the
conversation to be more personal, as it’s just the two of you engaging in
dialogue. When it comes to participating in dialogue with one other person,
you need to be able to approach people differently as individuals.
Unlike a group setting, your conversation will be focused on one person,
which means you can cater the topic and type of conversation to be one
that’s suitable for them. This is why it’s beneficial for you to consider who
you’re talking to so that you can engage in small talk that captivates them,
makes them feel heard, and gives them a great impression of you!
Expanding Your Network
Whether you’re talking to a group of people or you’re talking to someone
one-on-one, it’s always wise to focus on expanding your network.
Networking doesn’t only have to be considered for your professional life, as
networking can be valuable for multiple aspects of your life. You never
know how someone can help you in your life, as well as you don’t know
what you can do for them in return.
Regardless of who you’re communicating with, you need to be open to
networking with them. Telling people more about yourself is valuable for
your networking, as people know whether they can help you in life.
Whether it’s for a professional or personal matter, we all need some help in
life, and networking with the people you meet can help you in the long run.
CHAPTER 10
Going From Small Talk to
Meaningful Conversations
"Conversation isn't about proving a point; true conversation is about going
on a journey with the people you are speaking with." – Ricky Maye
When you learn how to utilize small talk in conversations, you need to have
the ultimate goal of creating meaningful conversations. You want to have
communication with depth and meaning and this can only be achieved once
you break the ice with small talk. Small talk is merely the building block
that helps you to achieve meaningful and engaging conversations with other
people. You need to start somewhere by using small talk to break the ice
and get comfortable with each other.
It’s valuable to find ways to turn your small talk strategies and techniques
into meaningful conversations. How can you lead general conversation to
something much deeper and meaningful? Discovering how you can do this
will help you to build the emotional connections you desire in your life, as
well as it will make you one hell of a conversationalist.
How to Elevate Small Talk
When you engage in small talk, you need to know how to use it with an
open mind. The objective of your conversation shouldn’t be to just talk
about the weather or current events in the world, but it’s also to get closer to
the person you’re talking to. You need to start small talk with the goal of
initiating more depth in your conversation. These are some ways to elevate
your small talk so that it transports you to more meaningful conversations
that build connections.
Ask the Right Questions
We’ve established that questions are a very crucial part of small talk, but are
you asking the right questions? To have a meaningful and deep
conversation, you need to be able to ask thought provoking questions that
influence a deeper conversation. It’s time to steer away from the cliche,
overused stock questions such as, “Where are you from?” and “What is
your occupation?” You need to have deeper questions that can result in
interesting answers that teach you more about the person you’re talking to.
These are some examples of suitable thought provoking questions to ask:
What’s something exciting you’ve done today?
What is a dream or passion that you have?
When was the last time you tried something new?
When you’re thinking of questions to ask for a deep conversation, get
creative and think outside of the box. You will notice that your conversation
partner is more engaged in the conversation when they’re asked different
questions they’ve never heard. However, when you do ask these different,
thought provoking questions, you must ensure that you aren’t asking
anything too personal or inappropriate. Your priority should be to make the
other person feel comfortable within your small talk.
Look for Opportunities to Connect
The best way to accomplish meaningful conversation from small talk is by
actively seeking opportunities to connect with others. During your small
talk, you will come across moments in conversation that are perfect
opportunities for you to connect. It’s important for you to identify these
golden opportunities. This how you can use these opportunities to connect
to the person talking to:
Relate to them. When your conversation partner says something that
you relate to or something that may resonate with you, it’s important to
dive deeper in that topic. When you relate to each other about
something, it will bring you closer and instigate a deeper, more
interesting conversation. You will find you develop a bond while
talking about a topic that connects you.
Tell a story. Storytelling is a great way to bring more depth to a
conversation. When you hear them talking about something that
you’ve experienced, you can do more than just say, “Same here,” or
“Me, too.” You can go the extra mile by telling an interesting story that
captivates the other person’s attention. Telling your story may inspire
them to share their own stories, which helps you learn more about
them.
Ask more. Sometimes people talk about a topic briefly, but they
actually want to talk about it in more depth. If you can tell someone
wants to talk about something, or they bring up a topic that’s
interesting, you should consider asking them more questions about the
matter. This allows them to share more about a matter, which helps
you to get into a deeper, more meaningful conversation.
There are opportunities in every conversation to find more depth and
information. You don’t have to settle for surface level conversations, as
small talk can branch out to something much greater. For instance, you may
find that you have something in common, or you could have an interesting
story related to what the other person has to say.
Don’t Strive for One-Off Conversations
You may find yourself excited because you've engaged in successful small
talk, but you know that this is just an ounce of conversation with this
individual. As you leave the conversation, you don’t ask for their name,
number, or any details, so you know you won’t see them again. You may
even find that your conversation leaves on an awkward or dull note, which
makes you think that you probably won’t have another conversation with
this individual.
When you’re starting small talk with someone for the first time, your
objective should be to have many more connections with them. You want to
build connections with people and get on their good side, which can only be
accomplished through multiple conversations. This makes it crucial to end
your small talk conversation on a high note. You can even mention you
want to talk to them again soon.
Leaving a conversation on this note will ensure that you have more
conversations with this person in the future. Although your first
conversation may not be deep and meaningful, if it ends well, it will
influence many conversations in the future. This is what makes the first
conversation so valuable.
The Power of Small Talk
Small talk is a lot more powerful and valuable than you may give it credit
for. It’s important to realize that small talk is more than just general
conversation, as it is the foundation of a much deeper conversation. When
you utilize small talk to the best of your ability, you’re able to take back
control over your social life. Mastering small talk will transform your social
life in the following ways:
Finding self-confidence: The art of small talk is essentially having
confidence in yourself. Being able to get to the level where you can
talk to anyone about anything displays a high level of confidence.
When you master small talk and learn how to talk to everyone, it will
grow your confidence. The whole process of learning how to put
yourself out there will slowly build up your confidence and self-
esteem.
Building strong connections: Unfortunately, we can’t excel or find
happiness in life all by ourselves. Whether we like to admit it or not,
we need other people. It’s valuable to know how to build connections
for all aspects of our lives. You may want to learn how to use small
talk to land your dream partner, you want your new conversational
skills to dazzle your boss and colleagues at work, or you’re suffering
from loneliness and you need to mingle with new people. No matter
what type of connection you desire, mastering small talk will help you
to get there.
Learning about people: Not only does small talk help you to build
connections, but it also helps you to learn more about people. You get
to learn about each person more specifically, but you also discover
more about people in general. You get to discover new information
about the people in your life, which helps you to communicate better.
You also begin to understand how nonverbal communication works,
which will revolutionize the way you see things.
You can experience all of these drastic improvements and benefits in your
life if you work toward mastering small talk. You can enjoy life so much
more just by improving your social life alone. We all need to feel like
people want to talk to us; otherwise it can feel like a really lonely life.
Small talk is a way to spread your friendliness and receive love in return.
Conclusion
We can never get anywhere in life if we don’t have the appropriate
conversations. To learn more about others, build emotional connections,
excel in your career, and make a good impression, you need to be able to
engage in effective communication. Mastering small talk is a big part of this
experience.
When you’re able to have small talk with people, you will see how it opens
up the door for various opportunities for conversation. You no longer have
to feel like an outsider in group conversation or worry about how to get
someone to like you. All you need to do is use the small talk tips and tricks
provided to you through this book. Although it may seem like an overload
of information, it is actually quite simple and achievable at the end of the
day.
You need to make sure you’re making good use of questions, as they can do
wonders for your small talk game. Asking other people questions during
conversations doesn’t only help you to discover more about them, but it
also influences them to be more engaged in the conversation. Ask thought-
provoking questions, be curious, and even ask follow-up questions to show
how interested you are in them.
Of course, small talk is only successful when both parties are participating.
Along with asking questions, you need to open up about yourself as well.
Let your conversation partner in so that they can understand you. If you’re
building connections, it’s valuable to open up and get vulnerable. This will
make people warm up to you as they can see you’re a genuine and
vulnerable individual, which will make them feel comfortable to talk to you
in future.
The way you talk to people is also so important to consider. You need to be
honest, respectful, and empathetic toward others. If you keep this in mind as
you communicate, you will create great impressions on others. It’s also
important to realize that there are many nonverbal cues you can give.
Consider your body language and the message it’s sending others.
Above all, have fun with it. Don’t take small talk so seriously, as it can be
an enjoyable experience for you and the people you talk to. Although you
should apply all of these tips to your conversations, you shouldn’t let them
alter your personality. You still need to be yourself and let people know you
for who you are. Now it’s time to get out there and practice those small talk
skills!
